const SAP_QUESTIONS = [{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A multinational financial firm manages 240 AWS accounts with strict data residency requirements: EU customer data must remain in eu-west-1, Asia-Pacific in ap-southeast-1, and US data in us-east-1. They need centralized security governance while allowing business units self-service account creation. What architecture ensures data residency compliance?","options":["A. Single AWS account with IAM-based regional restrictions and S3 bucket policies","B. AWS Organizations with region-restrictive SCPs per OU, Control Tower account factory with region guardrails, and automated Config conformance packs","C. Separate AWS Organizations per region with no cross-organization networking","D. AWS Config rules that detect non-compliant resources and trigger automatic remediation"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Organizations with OUs by region allows SCPs (deny aws:RequestedRegion outside approved) to enforce data sovereignty preventively. Control Tower ensures new accounts inherit guardrails. Config packs verify compliance."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"An enterprise has 180 AWS accounts across 12 business units with hybrid identity via Active Directory. They need consistent IAM baseline policies, permission boundaries enforcing maximum privilege per role, and audit trails for all cross-account assume-role activity. Which combination is most effective?","options":["A. AWS SSO with identity center, SCPs for baseline, CloudTrail logging","B. SCPs defining max permissions per OU, permission boundaries at account level, resource-based policies for SSO principals only, organization CloudTrail","C. IAM roles in each account with trust relationships to AD","D. AWS Cognito for identity federation"],"answer":1,"explain":"SCPs + permission boundaries + CloudTrail provide preventive, permissive, and detective controls combined. Permission boundaries act as hard ceiling regardless of attached policies."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization uses AWS Organizations with 250+ accounts spanning 8 OUs. You need to enforce all RDS databases encrypt, all data backed up daily, and all S3 buckets have versioning, with exceptions for sandboxes and dev. What's the most maintainable approach?","options":["A. SCPs denying unencrypted resources; Config rules with remediation","B. Control Tower guardrails for preventive controls, Config conformance packs with OU-based exceptions, auto-remediation","C. CloudFormation StackSets deploying Config rules with manual exemptions","D. Service Catalog templates pre-configured for encryption"],"answer":1,"explain":"Control Tower guardrails are AWS-maintained and versioned. Conformance packs allow exceptions by OU. Config remediation automates fixing. Scales automatically to new accounts."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 200-account AWS environment needs three security domains: Production (PCI-DSS), Protected Health (HIPAA), Development (no compliance). Domains must never allow cross-domain network traffic. Each domain needs isolated billing and compliance reporting. How should OUs be structured?","options":["A. Single OU with tags and Config rules","B. Three root OUs: Prod-OU, PHI-OU, Dev-OU; SCPs blocking cross-OU assume-role and VPC peering/TGW between OUs; separate billing per domain","C. Separate AWS Organizations per domain","D. Mix of OU hierarchy and tags with SCPs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Three root OUs maintains single billing relationship while SCPs enforce identity and network isolation for regulatory compliance."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization has 340 accounts requiring consolidated AWS Bills with chargeback to business units by cost center, project ID, and environment. You need real-time cost visibility and anomaly detection. What's the best architecture?","options":["A. AWS Billing Conductor with custom groups, Cost Explorer, CloudWatch anomaly detector","B. Cost Allocation Tags via SCPs, Cost and Usage Reports to S3, Athena queries, Lambda anomaly detection","C. Organizations billing consolidation with detailed CUR to S3, QuickSight dashboards per BU, Compute Optimizer for rightsizing","D. SCPs enforce tagging, then use Cost Explorer"],"answer":2,"explain":"Organizations consolidates billing automatically. Detailed CUR provides granular data. S3+QuickSight enables self-service BI with full flexibility. Compute Optimizer adds rightsizing."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"An enterprise is migrating 150 AWS accounts from three unrelated Organizations into a single Organization for unified governance. Legacy Organizations use different tagging, naming, and SCPs. What's the safest sequence?","options":["A. Bulk invite all accounts, then apply Control Tower","B. Create target OU structure, migrate one-per-BU with tag reconciliation, gradually apply read-only guardrails first, validate with Config packs","C. Use AWS Migration Accelerator to auto-consolidate","D. Keep separate, link via AWS RAM"],"answer":1,"explain":"Bulk migration risks breaking workloads. Phased approach: (1) tag reconciliation, (2) per-BU invitation, (3) detective guardrails, (4) validation, (5) preventive SCPs."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization operates 200 accounts and needs to implement Control Tower with existing custom CloudFormation guardrails already deployed. Which approach minimizes disruption?","options":["A. Deploy fresh CT, override custom guardrails","B. Audit for equivalence, decommission duplicates, import accounts, add CT guardrails for additional coverage","C. Keep CloudFormation, add CT guardrails in detective-only mode","D. Use AWS Migration Accelerator"],"answer":1,"explain":"Audit ensures equivalence before decommissioning. Control Tower becomes single source of truth. Gradual decommissioning prevents governance gaps."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A healthcare organization with 120 AWS accounts needs HIPAA compliance. Each account processes different patient data. They need per-account audit logs, centralized analysis, tamper-evident logging, and compliance evidence. What's the best architecture?","options":["A. CloudTrail per account to S3 with MFA delete","B. Organization CloudTrail with MFA delete, Object Lock, log file validation, HIPAA conformance pack, Config aggregator","C. Security Hub with HIPAA standards","D. CloudWatch Logs Insights"],"answer":1,"explain":"Organization CloudTrail centralizes with chain-of-custody. Object Lock (read-only) + MFA delete achieves compliance-grade immutability. Log file validation detects tampering. Config aggregator proves compliance."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization has 95 accounts across 5 business units with different cost allocation needs and autonomy. CFO needs consolidated billing, departments need independent tracking. Production must have hard isolation from development. What's the optimal structure?","options":["A. Flat OU with all accounts, use tags","B. One OU per BU with nested prod/dev OUs; use cost tags within each; SCPs limit cross-OU networking","C. Single prod OU, single dev OU; use tags for BU allocation","D. Shared dev OU per BU"],"answer":1,"explain":"Nested OUs mirror organizational structure. Sub-OUs allow different governance for prod (stricter) vs dev (permissive). Cost tags enable fine-grained chargeback."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"An organization is implementing Service Catalog for self-service provisioning across 50 accounts. Business units provision databases, VPCs, compute. You need to enforce tagging, control costs, and prevent non-approved services. What's the architecture?","options":["A. Portfolio per BU with IAM policies, launch constraints enforcing tags, SCPs blocking non-catalog","B. Central portfolio with approved products, launch constraints with cost tag requirements, SCPs deny non-catalog services, CloudFormation custom resources validate business logic","C. Delegated portfolio administration per BU","D. No restrictions, rely on Config remediation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Central portfolio maintains consistency. Launch constraints bind specific IAM role. SCPs prevent workarounds. CloudFormation custom resources validate business logic."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization has 180 accounts with AWS SSO from Active Directory. You need to ensure all humans assume roles, services use temporary credentials, and cross-account access follows least privilege. How should you architect IAM?","options":["A. SSO for humans with permission sets, IAM roles for services, external IDs for cross-account","B. SSO groups to permission sets, SCP block IAM users, resource policies for SSO principals only, cross-account roles require MFA","C. Lambda service-linked roles for services","D. Cognito federation"],"answer":1,"explain":"SCP blocks IAM users enforces temporary credentials everywhere. Resource-based policies restrict to SSO principals. MFA on cross-account roles adds security layer."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"An enterprise with 220 accounts needs to share a VPC Transit Gateway across 15 accounts via RAM. The TGW needs to support hybrid on-premises connectivity via Direct Connect. How should this be architected?","options":["A. TGW in network account, share via RAM, traffic routes through TGW","B. TGW with Direct Connect attachment, share via RAM, each account VPC attaches to TGW with own subnets","C. TGW in each account with peering","D. VPN concentrator shared via PrivateLink"],"answer":1,"explain":"TGW in network account with DX attachment. AWS RAM shares to 15 accounts automatically. Each account VPCs attach enabling transitive routing."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization manages 200+ accounts and needs to enforce compliance: all EC2 instances have detailed monitoring (1-min intervals), all RDS have 30+ day backup retention, all S3 have centralized logging. Which approach is most scalable?","options":["A. CloudFormation StackSets per requirement","B. Control Tower guardrails preventive/detective, Config conformance pack with remediation, org S3 bucket for centralized logging with Config aggregator","C. Org-wide Config rules with SNS and Lambda","D. Service Catalog templates with Config verification"],"answer":1,"explain":"Control Tower guardrails are AWS-maintained. Conformance packs deploy Config rules at org scale. Config remediation automates fixing. Scales to any account count."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"An organization with 160 accounts enabling CloudTrail organization trail needs: immutable logs, 7-year retention, per-account cost attribution, and <1s forensic query latency. What's the architecture?","options":["A. S3 object lock governance, lifecycle to Glacier, Athena queries","B. S3 MFA delete + versioning, log file validation, Intelligent-Tiering, CloudTrail Lake for forensics, S3 Storage Lens for cost attribution","C. Per-account trails with replication to central","D. S3 object lock compliance mode, Athena+Lakeformation"],"answer":1,"explain":"MFA delete + versioning prevents accidental deletion. CloudTrail Lake provides sub-second query latency. Intelligent-Tiering optimizes 7-year costs. Storage Lens attributes costs."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization has 3-tier OU hierarchy (Root > Division > Department > Team) with 250+ accounts. Different tiers need different governance. How should SCPs be structured?","options":["A. Single set at root affecting all","B. SCPs at each level: root (baseline security), division (residency), department (cost controls), team (service restrictions); union inheritance","C. SCPs only at leaf OUs","D. One SCP per BU"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hierarchical SCPs apply union-of-denies: root denies risky services, division denies non-approved regions, department denies expensive services, team denies specific services. Scalable per tier."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"An organization consolidating 5 separate AWS accounts into single Organization has existing CloudTrail trails in 2 accounts and custom Config rules across all. What's the safest consolidation?","options":["A. Immediate org trail, disable account trails","B. Create org trail parallel to account trails, validate 2 weeks, disable account trails; migrate Config rules to packs gradually via aggregator","C. Keep trails forever for redundancy","D. Disable before creating org trail"],"answer":1,"explain":"Parallel validation proves org trail works. Gradual Config migration prevents governance gaps. Organization trail eventually provides single source of truth."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 140-account organization needs encryption for all data stores (RDS, DynamoDB, S3, EBS). BUs have different key needs: AWS-managed, customer-managed, or HSM. How should this be implemented?","options":["A. Single KMS key in central account via RAM","B. Per-account customer-managed keys; central account for HSM; Config detecting non-compliance","C. Per-OU SCPs per BU strategy; per-account keys; CT guardrails; Config with remediation","D. Secrets Manager for key management"],"answer":2,"explain":"Per-OU SCPs allow different strategies (AWS-managed vs customer-managed vs HSM) based on BU needs. Per-account KMS provides isolation. Control Tower + Config ensures compliance."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization manages 200+ accounts with Firewall Manager for org-wide firewall policies (WAF, security groups, network firewalls). Some accounts need stricter rules. How should policies be structured?","options":["A. Single policy set org-wide with Config exemptions","B. Policies per security domain (dev, prod, sensitive), applied via scope targeting OUs; exclusion list for exceptions; local policies extend (not override)","C. Root-level policies with account overrides","D. CloudFormation StackSets per account"],"answer":1,"explain":"Firewall Manager policy scope enables domain-specific policies. Exclusion lists exempt dev accounts. Local policies extend (additive) preventing security gaps."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization operates 250 accounts across 3 continents with GDPR residency. Requirements: data stays in-region, keys stay in-region, compliance audits per-region, global consolidated billing. What's the architecture?","options":["A. Single Orgs at global, EU/APAC/Americas as regional OUs, regional SCPs, regional keys, per-region Config aggregators","B. Separate Orgs per region with RAM federation","C. Accounts pinned to regions via SCP, global key","D. Tags enforce residency, Config detects"],"answer":0,"explain":"Single Organizations with regional OUs + SCPs achieves residency enforcement while maintaining consolidated billing and central governance."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"An organization with 95 accounts implementing RBAC via AWS SSO has custom permission sets per account, but 30% of permissions are identical. How should this be optimized?","options":["A. Union all permissions in each set","B. Create shared baseline permission set for all accounts, account-specific permission sets stack on top","C. Individual permission set per account","D. Use IAM Identity Center policy inheritance"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS SSO allows multiple permission sets assigned to same user in single account. Shared baseline + account-specific stacking avoids 30% duplication."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 180-account organization implementing Service Catalog for provisioning must prevent shadow IT. You must block direct resource creation while allowing catalog use. What's the best approach?","options":["A. SCPs deny all creation except catalog role","B. SCPs block IAM user creation; launch constraints bind specific role; resource policies allow only that role; Config detects non-catalog with remediation","C. Admin policies on all resources","D. StackSets prevent manual creation"],"answer":1,"explain":"SCP blocks IAM users, launch constraints bind role, resource policies restrict access, Config remediation terminates non-catalog resources. Prevents all shadow IT paths."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization manages 300+ accounts enforcing complex compliance for sensitive data (PII, PHI, payment cards). Requirements: encryption, logging, exfiltration monitoring. What's the best architecture?","options":["A. S3 Block Public Access, per-account CloudTrail, local Config, manual reviews","B. Macie for discovery/classification, org CloudTrail, immutable S3, GuardDuty for threat detection, SIEM via EventBridge","C. DLP via StackSets, per-account encryption SCPs, manual aggregation","D. Encrypted S3, access logging, CloudWatch alarms"],"answer":1,"explain":"Macie discovers data, GuardDuty detects exfiltration patterns, EventBridge streams to SIEM for real-time response. Provides full visibility and threat detection."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"An organization with 200 accounts needs to comply with requirement: no AWS secrets in code or environment variables. What's the best enforced architecture?","options":["A. Code review policies and SSO access","B. SCPs block IAM users, Secrets Manager for all secrets, resource policies restrict to service roles, CodeBuild pulls secrets at build time, CloudTrail logs access","C. Terraform encryption, Config detecting hardcoded","D. Parameter Store for config, Secrets Manager for secrets"],"answer":1,"explain":"SCP prevents long-term credentials. Secrets Manager stores all secrets. Resource policies grant access only to specific roles. CodeBuild retrieves at build time. Technologically enforced."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 120-account organization implementing auto-remediation for compliance violations. An S3 bucket created without encryption. What's the safest automated remediation approach?","options":["A. Config auto-remediation immediately enables encryption","B. Config detects, Lambda enables encryption, SNS notifies team for approval, implements after confirmation","C. Quarantine bucket with SCPs, manual remediation required","D. Lambda enables immediately, CloudTrail audit, manual review after"],"answer":1,"explain":"Auto-detection + enable + manual approval prevents accidentally breaking changes (e.g., breaking dev use cases) while maintaining automation benefits."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 170-account organization needs to enforce MFA for all human access to production accounts. Teams have different MFA requirements (TOTP, hardware keys, Okta). How to implement?","options":["A. SCPs deny assume-role without MFA, SSO with MFA, per-account IAM roles","B. Okta + SSO integration, permission sets with MFA conditions","C. Production OUs with SCPs denying assume-role without aws:MultiFactorAuthPresent, SSO with MFA, KMS-encrypted MFA seeds, CloudTrail verification","D. IAM policies requiring MFA in prod accounts"],"answer":2,"explain":"SCP denies assume-role without MFA (preventive). SSO enforces MFA at identity level. KMS encrypts MFA seeds. CloudTrail audits MFA usage. Ensures no human bypasses MFA."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 250-account organization needs least-privilege networking with VPCs in 5 regions. All inter-account traffic routes through centralized hubs per region, all internet traffic through egress firewalls. What's the architecture?","options":["A. VPC mesh, centralized NAT gateways","B. TGW per region with DX, cross-region TGW peering, centralized egress via network firewall","C. Central VPC peering hub","D. TGW per OU with cascading peering"],"answer":1,"explain":"TGW per region scales to 5000+ attachments. Network firewall provides centralized DLP inspection. TGW peering enables cross-region routing efficiently."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization manages 200+ accounts auditing 500+ GB/day CloudTrail logs. Needs: <1s forensic query latency, per-account cost attribution, 7-year compliance retention. What architecture meets requirements?","options":["A. S3 + CloudFront, Glacier after 30 days, Athena analysis","B. S3 partitioned by account/date, Intelligent-Tiering, CloudTrail Lake for forensics, S3 Storage Lens for attribution","C. CloudWatch Logs, Insights queries, 30-day default retention","D. Splunk via Kinesis Firehose"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudTrail Lake provides sub-second query latency. Intelligent-Tiering optimizes 7-year costs. S3 Storage Lens provides per-account attribution."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 160-account organization implementing change management requires all infrastructure changes through approval process before deployment. What's the enforcement architecture?","options":["A. SCPs block CloudFormation except via approved system","B. Service Catalog with approval workflows, SCPs block direct creation, Config rules enforce","C. CodePipeline with approval stages, CodeDeploy to members","D. All infrastructure via CloudFormation with peer review"],"answer":1,"explain":"Service Catalog provides approval workflows. SCPs prevent direct creation. Config rules detect non-catalog resources. Ensures all changes go through approval."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization has 180 accounts implementing chargeback with multi-dimensional allocation: business units, project IDs, teams, cost centers. Different services have different rules (compute per team, storage per BU). How to architect?","options":["A. Enforce 4 tags via SCPs, use Cost Allocation in billing, Cost Explorer grouping","B. Enforce tags, CUR to S3, Athena + Redshift allocation, per-OU chargeback","C. Organizations + SCPs, detailed CUR to S3, Lambda cost engine with service-specific rules, cost reports to FinOps","D. Billing Conductor with custom groups"],"answer":2,"explain":"Lambda cost allocation engine applies service-specific rules that built-in tools can't. Cost and Usage Report has raw data for custom logic at scale."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 200-account organization implementing Lake Formation for data lake serving 5 BUs with different access. Some data restricted to units, some shared. How to design?","options":["A. Single catalog, database per BU, table permissions per unit","B. Central account with RAM, databases per BU in S3, IAM-based access","C. Central Lake Formation catalog, databases per BU, table-level permissions via cross-account roles, shared data accessible via permissions","D. Separate Lake Formation per BU"],"answer":2,"explain":"Centralized Lake Formation with cross-account roles enables fine-grained table-level access. Shared databases accessible to multiple BUs via resource permissions."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 140-account organization runs hybrid with on-premises DCs via multiple DX connections. HA and failover needed across 3 AWS regions. How should this be architected?","options":["A. Single DX to primary, Route 53 failover to secondaries","B. Two DX (1 Gbps each) to primary for redundancy, VGW peering on-prem failover","C. Redundant DX per region (min 2 each), different edge locations, BGP AS_PATH prepending, TGW per region with peering, on-prem BGP peers all DX","D. Single 10 Gbps DX with automatic routing"],"answer":2,"explain":"Multiple DX per region with BGP AS_PATH prepending provides active-active with automatic failover. TGW peering enables cross-region routing."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"An organization with 210 accounts implementing AppConfig for distributed configuration management. Different teams need different configs (feature flags, endpoints, timeouts). How should AppConfig be structured?","options":["A. Single application with environments per team","B. Applications per BU, environments per team/region, profiles per service, IAM roles restrict team access","C. Centralized in management account, cross-account RAM access, applications per BU, IAM roles per team","D. AppConfig per account, manual sync"],"answer":2,"explain":"Centralized AppConfig via AWS RAM enables cross-account access with fine-grained IAM-based restrictions per team. Single source of truth for configurations."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 180-account healthcare organization implementing HIPAA audit logging needs: all API calls logged, logs immutable, compliance team only access for 6+ years, quarterly reports, encryption proof. What's the architecture?","options":["A. CloudTrail to S3 with MFA delete, lifecycle to Glacier","B. Organization CloudTrail, S3 Object Lock (compliance mode), KMS encryption in compliance team's account, log file validation, quarterly reports via Config, access logging","C. Per-account CloudTrail with replication","D. CloudTrail + Splunk integration"],"answer":1,"explain":"Object Lock compliance mode provides immutability. KMS in compliance team's account proves key ownership. Log file validation detects tampering. Access logging proves controls. Quarterly reports prove compliance."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 165-account organization implementing automated incident response: GuardDuty detects threat, system should isolate resource, preserve logs, alert team. What's the architecture?","options":["A. GuardDuty → CloudWatch Events → Lambda isolates resource, SNS alerts","B. Org GuardDuty with delegated admin, findings → EventBridge → Step Functions: Lambda isolates (revoke creds, remove SG), EBS snapshot for forensics, SNS alerts, Systems Manager collects logs","C. GuardDuty → Security Hub → manual remediation","D. GuardDuty per account with local automation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Org GuardDuty + EventBridge + Step Functions orchestrates multi-step response while preserving forensic evidence. Systems Manager ensures log collection."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 195-account organization implementing cross-account backup/DR for production databases (RDS, DynamoDB) in 20 primary accounts to central DR account with automatic failover capability. How to architect?","options":["A. Local RDS backups, manual copy to DR, manual RDS replica promotion","B. AWS Backup with copy rules to central DR, cross-account IAM roles, automated DynamoDB on-demand backups with replication, pre-configured restore role in DR","C. RDS read replicas in DR, Global Tables for DynamoDB","D. Backup agent per account, centralized backup server"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Backup copy rules automate replication. Cross-account roles enable service execution. Pre-configured restore role minimizes RTO. Handles heterogeneous DB types."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 200-account organization needs to enforce data classification and prevent exfiltration. All data classified (public, internal, confidential, restricted), attempts blocked/alerted. What's the architecture?","options":["A. Macie for classification, S3 bucket policies block unclassified, Config detects","B. Macie for discovery/classification, SCPs block S3 GetObject on unclassified, GuardDuty detects bulk downloads, DLP Gateway blocks network exfil","C. Macie tagging, IAM policies per classification","D. Manual classification, Config enforcement, Lambda remediation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Macie discovers data (prevention), GuardDuty detects exfiltration patterns (detection), DLP Gateway blocks at network level (response). Defense-in-depth approach."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 220-account organization consolidating VPCs from multiple legacy environments into hub-and-spoke. 50 legacy VPCs across regions with different IP ranges and security group configs. What's the safest approach?","options":["A. Bulk migrate all VPCs to TGW, test after cutover","B. Create TGW infrastructure, validate 5 pilot VPCs for 2 weeks, waves of 20 VPCs/week with pre-flight validation (IP overlap, SG audit), post-migration testing, rollback per wave","C. Create new VPCs, migrate apps via database tools","D. VPC peering interim, plan TGW migration later"],"answer":1,"explain":"Phased migration with pilot validation and per-wave rollback plans minimizes blast radius. Pre-flight validation prevents IP conflicts and security issues."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization has 240 accounts implementing cross-account backup and recovery for Kubernetes (EKS) clusters with 20 primary clusters. What's the architecture?","options":["A. EKS etcd snapshots in account, no cross-account","B. Velero deployed in each cluster, snapshots to central S3 via cross-account role, cross-account restore role pre-configured in DR","C. AWS Backup for EKS with central account","D. Container image scanning, registry replication, assume stateless"],"answer":1,"explain":"Velero captures cluster state, persistent volumes, and application config. Cross-account role enables rapid recovery. Standard Kubernetes backup approach."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 175-account organization implementing encryption key management needs: customer-managed KMS in each account for isolation, but centralized key rotation/audit from security account, and DR keys. How to architect?","options":["A. Customer-managed KMS per account, all trust security account root","B. Customer-managed KMS per account replicated to security for DR, assume key admin role for rotation","C. Multi-region KMS per account with auto-rotation, security account read-only audit role (GetKeyPolicy, ListKeys), central CloudTrail","D. HSM-backed keys in central cluster via PrivateLink"],"answer":2,"explain":"Multi-region KMS + automatic rotation + read-only audit role achieves centralized key management without granting admin access."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 205-account organization implementing Trusted Advisor checks org-wide with centralized reporting and remediation recommendations. What's the architecture?","options":["A. Trusted Advisor per account","B. Business plan minimum per account","C. Organization Support plan with API refresh, findings → S3 → Athena queries, QuickSight dashboard per OU","D. No organizational aggregation"],"answer":2,"explain":"Organizations Support plan enables API refresh across accounts. S3 + Athena + QuickSight provides scalable analysis at 200+ account level."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 180-account organization implementing Systems Manager Fleet Manager for managing 10,000+ EC2 instances across accounts and on-premises. What's the architecture?","options":["A. Session Manager per account with local patching","B. Central Systems Manager as aggregator, cross-account IAM roles, central patching via SSM documents, hybrid activation for on-prem, Patch Manager compliance dashboard","C. Automation per account with local workflows","D. Independent per account with manual sync"],"answer":1,"explain":"Central Systems Manager with cross-account IAM roles aggregates fleet. Hybrid Activation includes on-premises servers. Patch Manager provides central compliance visibility."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 185-account organization adopting AWS Outposts for on-premises infrastructure. How to integrate into multi-account Organizations architecture?","options":["A. Separate AWS account via Direct Connect","B. Outposts in Organizations with own OU, TGW on-prem connection, hybrid deployment via IaC, SSO extending to Outposts","C. Managed separately outside Organizations","D. Extension of primary cloud account"],"answer":1,"explain":"Outposts in Organizations with TGW on-premises connection enables consistent hybrid governance, billing, and unified infrastructure as code."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 200-account financial organization implementing FinSpace for financial data management. Different BUs have different regulatory requirements. How to architect?","options":["A. Single environment, data partitioned per BU via IAM","B. Dataset per BU with cross-BU sharing via FinSpace permissions, centralized ingestion via Kinesis/S3, BU workspaces with restricted access, cross-account IAM roles","C. Separate FinSpace per BU for isolation","D. Single account, BUs access via API with tags"],"answer":1,"explain":"FinSpace dataset per BU with fine-grained permissions enables regulatory isolation while allowing controlled sharing between units."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 195-account organization migrating from on-premises CA-signed certificates to AWS ACM. 5,000+ services depend on these certificates. How to manage migration?","options":["A. Bulk import CA certs to ACM in primary account","B. Import CA key to ACM in security account, cross-account IAM roles, enable auto-renewal, migrate services in 200/week waves with validation, dual-cert setup during transition","C. Import per account for isolation with sync","D. Use PrivateCA for issue"],"answer":1,"explain":"Phased migration with dual-cert setup and per-wave validation minimizes outage risk for 5000+ services depending on certs."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 205-account organization implementing continuous Config compliance monitoring. Configuration drift must be detected within 1 hour. What's the architecture?","options":["A. Config per account with central aggregator","B. Org-wide Config via Control Tower with 1-hour recorder frequency, multi-region aggregator, conformance packs, non-compliant → EventBridge → SNS alerts and Systems Manager remediation","C. Continuous Config recording, per-account analysis, quarterly reviews","D. 1-hour snapshots to S3, Lambda analysis"],"answer":1,"explain":"1-hour recorder + conformance packs + EventBridge automation detects and remediates drift within 1-hour target window automatically."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization with 310 accounts needs sub-second cost attribution for 500+ services. Different business models apply per service (consumption, reserved capacity, hybrid). How to architect?","options":["A. Cost Allocation Tags with Cost Explorer grouping","B. Detailed CUR partitioned by service, Redshift data warehouse with dimensional schema (service, BU, account, time), BI tools with row-level security","C. Billing Conductor with service-specific groups and custom pricing","D. S3 bucketing by cost center, Athena cost analysis"],"answer":1,"explain":"Redshift dimensional schema enables complex cost allocation queries that CUR export + Athena cannot support. Row-level security isolates BUs' cost data."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 280-account organization implementing Grafana across hybrid (AWS + on-premises). Different teams need visibility into own resources only. Central team needs org-wide view. How to architect?","options":["A. CloudWatch agent on all instances, export to Grafana via API","B. Grafana Cloud for managed service, AWS data source with cross-account IAM roles, on-prem agents send metrics, team folders with RBAC","C. Central Grafana EC2 with SSH access per team","D. Per-team Grafana instances with data syncing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Grafana Cloud managed service scales automatically. Cross-account IAM roles aggregate AWS data. Team folders with RBAC provide isolation while central dashboard shows enterprise view."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 225-account organization implements automated account decommissioning: old accounts must be deleted, data archived 7 years, billing consolidated. Process involves 50+ account deletions monthly. How to automate?","options":["A. Manual AWS account suspension, data export","B. AWS Batch jobs for data export to central S3, Config compliance check, close account via AWS Organizations API","C. Automation account with Systems Manager, scheduled daily: identify deletable accounts (via tag), backup via AWS Backup, clean resources per deletion SCP, close via org API","D. CloudFormation deletion roles per account"],"answer":2,"explain":"Scheduled Systems Manager automation with Config compliance checks ensures safe, consistent deletion. Central S3 archive enables 7-year retention. No manual operator required."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 190-account organization with 15 teams implementing Spot Fleet for HPC workloads. Different teams have different cost targets and capacity needs. How to manage?","options":["A. Single Spot Fleet shared by all teams","B. Per-team Spot Fleet with capacity reservations per team, allocation strategy (lowest-price vs diversified), AWS Batch for job queueing, cost tracking per team via tags","C. On-Demand for reliability","D. Reserved Instances per team"],"answer":1,"explain":"Per-team Spot Fleets with capacity reservations ensure isolation. AWS Batch manages queue globally. Diversified allocation reduces Spot interruption risk for critical jobs."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 200-account organization implementing multi-region disaster recovery for databases. RPO must be <1 minute, RTO <15 minutes. 150 databases across 3 regions. How to architect?","options":["A. Read replicas per region, Route 53 health checks, manual promotion","B. Aurora Global Database for MySQL/PostgreSQL (RPO <1s), DMS continuous replication for others, Route 53 health check → Lambda promotes read replica, Systems Manager activation for data validation","C. Database snapshots every hour","D. Backup vaults with cross-region replication"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aurora Global DB achieves RPO <1s natively. DMS continuous replication handles others. Lambda + Route 53 enables automated <15min RTO promotion process."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 240-account organization implementing LakeFormation for PII data governance. PII must not be accessed outside 2 principal geographies. How to enforce?","options":["A. S3 bucket policy block public access","B. Lake Formation table permissions via cross-account roles with geo-restriction tags, Macie + EventBridge block non-geo access attempts, log table access","C. Databases per geography, manual access review","D. IAM policies with IP restrictions"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lake Formation table-level permissions via geo-tagged roles. Macie detects PII access from outside permitted geos. EventBridge alerts and blocks."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 170-account organization implements DMS (Database Migration Service) to migrate 80 Oracle on-premises databases to Aurora on AWS. Minimal downtime (<5 mins), 24/7 operation, current production load 10 Gbps. What's the architecture?","options":["A. Single DMS replication instance, serial migration","B. Dedicated DMS task per database, parallel instances, continuous replication weeks prior, LOB chunking for large migrations, CDC during final cutover with brief app pause, validation per database before committing","C. AWS DataSync with custom Oracle export","D. Manual Oracle export to RDS"],"answer":1,"explain":"Parallel DMS tasks handle 80 databases concurrently. Weeks of continuous replication enables brief final cutover. CDC ensures consistency during cutover moment."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 185-account healthcare organization implementing SFTP gateway on AWS for on-premises partner data exchanges. HIPAA requires encryption in transit and at rest, audit trails, per-partner access control, weekly rotation of credentials. How to architect?","options":["A. EC2 running OpenSSH with user accounts","B. AWS Transfer Family (SFTP) in VPC with private ELB, LDAP auth to on-premises AD, S3 backend with encryption+versioning, CloudTrail logging all transfers, automated credential rotation via Secrets Manager + Lambda","C. Internet-facing FTP server","D. Partner-provided SFTP servers"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Transfer Family provides managed SFTP. LDAP auth integrates with existing AD. S3 encryption+versioning meets HIPAA. Secrets Manager + Lambda automates credential rotation."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 210-account organization managing 50,000+ EC2 instances implements automated patching across all accounts and regions. Windows & Linux, monthly patches, 99.95% uptime requirement during patching window. How to architect?","options":["A. Run Command per account, manual batching","B. Systems Manager Patch Manager with cross-account role, maintenance windows per region (staggered), auto-reboot with health check groups (ASG, NLB target deregistration), rollback groups if errors detected","C. EC2 ImageBuilder for automated AMI patching","D. Per-account manual patching schedule"],"answer":1,"explain":"Systems Manager Patch Manager with health check groups enables rolling updates maintaining uptime. Staggered windows across regions distribute load. Auto-reboot with target deregistration ensures graceful updates."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 220-account organization implementing AppStream 2.0 for 5,000+ distributed workforce to access on-premises applications without VPN. Low-latency is critical. How to architect?","options":["A. Single AppStream 2.0 fleet in primary region","B. Regional fleets in 4 major regions with connection preference based on latency, hybrid gateway for on-premises app routing via Direct Connect, cross-region user/fleet profile replication, load balancing via Route 53 latency policy","C. AppStream + Site-to-Site VPN","D. Desktop AMI shared via Systems Manager Session Manager"],"answer":1,"explain":"Regional fleets with latency routing enable low-latency access. Hybrid gateway routes to on-premises. Profile replication ensures user experience consistency across regions."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 200-account organization implements EventBridge to orchestrate 500+ microservices across AWS and on-premises. Services have variable latency (10ms to 5s). How to ensure reliable event delivery and prevent cascading failures?","options":["A. EventBridge → SQS → Lambda","B. EventBridge with Dead-Letter Queues per service, exponential backoff, Rule-based routing with retry policies (max 2 hours), Circuit breaker patterns via Lambda, monitoring via X-Ray tracing","C. Single EventBridge rule, async processing","D. SNS for pub/sub, per-service retry logic"],"answer":1,"explain":"DLQ + exponential backoff + time limits prevent message loss. Rule-based retry policies vary by service latency. X-Ray tracks failures across hybrid infrastructure."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 195-account organization implements KMS key management with cross-account key sharing for encryption. 500+ keys across accounts. Key audit and rotation must be centralized, but deletion requires approval from account owner. How to architect?","options":["A. All keys in central account","B. Keys per account, central CloudTrail for audit, cross-account assume role for rotation, per-account approval for deletion via Lambda approval gate, KMS key policy allows both account and central key admin","C. Keys in each account, S3 replication for backup","D. Secrets Manager for key management"],"answer":1,"explain":"Per-account keys provide isolation. Cross-account assume role enables central rotation. Lambda approval gate honors deletion approval from account owner. Prevents rogue central admin from deleting keys."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 230-account organization implements Secrets Manager with 10,000+ secrets. Audit team must see secret names and rotation status (never values), developers access only their app's secrets, emergency access via approval gate. How to architect?","options":["A. Secrets per account, IAM policies per developer","B. Secrets Manager cross-account resource policy, resource-based policies by secret (read-only for audit, read-only-values for devs), approval role for emergency access, CloudTrail logs all access","C. Central account with secrets for all teams","D. Parameter Store for non-sensitive, Secrets Manager for sensitive"],"answer":1,"explain":"Resource-based policies enable fine-grained access (audit sees metadata, devs see values, approval gate for emergency). CloudTrail provides audit trail. Prevents privilege escalation via assume-role."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 175-account organization implementing AWS Marketplace for software procurement. Different BUs need independent Marketplace subscriptions, but central finance wants consolidated billing and license tracking. How to architect?","options":["A. Marketplace subscriptions per BU account, bulk billing","B. Marketplace subscriptions in member accounts with linked payment method to master account, subscription tracking tag + Config rule validation, cost allocation report per BU, quarterly renewal approval via Approval Group","C. Single central account subscription, distribute via API calls","D. Individual BU billing entirely separate"],"answer":1,"explain":"Marketplace subscriptions in member accounts enable BU independence, linked payment enables consolidated billing, Config rules track subscriptions, Approval Group centralizes renewal."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 205-account organization running Kubernetes (EKS) needs multi-cluster orchestration for resilience. 15 clusters across 3 regions. Cross-cluster load balancing, automated failover, state replication. How to architect?","options":["A. Individual clusters with Route 53 failover","B. EKS on EC2 + Fargate, Consul service mesh for cross-cluster service discovery, Global Accelerator for traffic distribution, EBS snapshots + Velero for state replication across clusters, RTO <5min failover","C. Single cluster across regions via EKS Anywhere","D. Per-cluster Helm deployments with manual sync"],"answer":1,"explain":"Consul provides distributed service mesh for cross-cluster discovery. Global Accelerator distributes traffic with health checks. Velero + EBS snapshots replicate application state."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 190-account organization implementing Compliance Manager for audits (SOC 2, PCI-DSS, HIPAA). 200+ requirements, different accounts have different compliance scope. How to aggregate and report?","options":["A. Config rules per requirement, per-account audit","B. Security Hub standard + Compliance Manager with scope filtering per control, Config aggregator for org-wide compliance score, automated reporting to audit team via QuickSight, exceptions via approval workflow","C. Manual control testing and spreadsheets","D. Separate audit tools per account"],"answer":1,"explain":"Security Hub + Compliance Manager aggregates. Config aggregator provides org-wide view. QuickSight enables automated reporting. Approval workflow tracks exceptions."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 215-account organization implements cost anomaly detection. Anomalies must trigger <5 min alerts to team, auto-remediation for known patterns, escalation for novel patterns. How to architect?","options":["A. Cost anomaly detector with SNS notifications","B. Cost Anomaly Detector rule per cost dimension (service, region, account), EventBridge rule routes alerts to Lambda (for auto-remediation of known patterns) and PagerDuty (for novel patterns), Cost Optimizer recommendations auto-applied if pattern recognized from prior incidents","C. Cost Explorer trending alerts, manual review","D. QuickSight anomaly detection with email"],"answer":1,"explain":"EventBridge + Lambda enables conditional routing: known patterns auto-remediate, novel patterns escalate. Cost Optimizer recommendations applied only for recognized patterns minimizes risk."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 200-account organization implements Amazon MWAA (Managed Apache Airflow) for ETL/data pipeline orchestration across 8 BUs. Each BU needs isolated environments, but shared metadata database and monitoring. How to architect?","options":["A. Single MWAA environment, DAGs per BU","B. MWAA environment per BU in member accounts, cross-account RDS for shared metadata, cross-account S3 logs for central monitoring, CloudWatch log group with cross-account role, IAM cross-account permissions for operators","C. Airflow on EC2 per BU","D. Glue jobs per BU instead of Airflow"],"answer":1,"explain":"MWAA per BU provides isolation and cost allocation. Shared RDS metadata enables coordination. Cross-account logs enable central monitoring without centralizing all environments."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 225-account organization implements automated resource tagging compliance. All resources must have 5 tags (CostCenter, Owner, Environment, Service, DataClass). Non-compliant resources must be auto-tagged within 24 hours or terminated. How to enforce?","options":["A. Config rules with SNS alerts, manual tagging","B. SCPs require tag keys at creation time (with deny for missing tags), Config non-compliance triggers Lambda that tags missing-tag resources (infers from resource properties, account tags, or defaults), 24h remediation window, Config compliance dashboard","C. IAM policies require tagging at user level","D. Tag enforcement via CloudFormation only"],"answer":1,"explain":"SCPs prevent creation without tags preventively. Lambda auto-tags within 24h window respecting human review (infers intelligently). Config dashboard shows progress toward compliance."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 185-account organization implementing least-privilege database access. DBA team needs emergent access to prod databases without standing permissions. Auditor needs to see what accessed what. How to architect for PostgreSQL on RDS?","options":["A. Database user per team member, manual grant/revoke","B. RDS Proxy with IAM authentication, temp IAM database auth tokens, RDS proxy logs SQL queries, Systems Manager Session Manager for DBA console access with approval, CloudTrail logs assumed roles","C. Master credentials shared with DBA team","D. VPN access to RDS endpoint, database user per engineer"],"answer":1,"explain":"RDS Proxy + IAM auth enables temporary credentials scoped to tokens with TTL. Session Manager + approval gate controls access. Query logging + CloudTrail provide audit trail."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 240-account organization manages 15,000+ Lambda functions across all accounts. Deployment must be automated, consistent across accounts, and auditable. Any function version change must log who, when, what. How to architect?","options":["A. S3 deployment zip per function, per-account Lambda execution","B. CodePipeline with cross-account deployment role, SAM/CloudFormation for IaC, CodeBuild tests per account, automated rollback on alarm, CloudTrail logs all deployments, per-version Lambda environment variable logs change requestor and timestamp","C. Lambda console deployments, SNS notifications","D. GitOps with per-account git branches"],"answer":1,"explain":"CodePipeline + CodeBuild + SAM ensures consistent, testable deployments. Cross-account role enables central orchestration. CloudTrail + environment variables provide complete audit trail of changes."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 195-account organization implements automated backup and restore testing for RDS databases across all accounts. 500+ databases. Restore testing must occur weekly without impacting production, generate test data report. How to architect?","options":["A. AWS Backup per account, manual testing","B. AWS Backup with cross-account backup vault, Systems Manager automation weekly: restore snapshot to test account → data validation Lambda → drop test DB, generates test report per database, SNS alerts on failures","C. CloudFormation snapshots with per-week Lambda execution","D. Manual restore testing quarterly"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Backup centralizes backup management. Systems Manager automation orchestrates weekly testing in isolated test account. Lambda validation + reporting ensures RTO/RPO verification."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization needs to interconnect 12 AWS regions with consistent, low-latency multi-region routing. 5,000+ services across regions, dynamic scaling. What's the most scalable architecture?","options":["A. VPC Peering between regions","B. Transit Gateway in each region with multi-region peering, dynamic routing protocol (BGP), shared services in secondary regions via Resource Access Manager","C. Global accelerator with static routing","D. Site-to-Site VPN between regions"],"answer":1,"explain":"TGW per region + multi-region peering scales to thousands of attachments per region. BGP enables dynamic routing for failover. RAM shares resources across regions automatically."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"A financial services firm needs active-active multi-region deployment with RPO = 0 (zero data loss). Customers expect <100ms latency globally. What architecture supports this?","options":["A. Primary region with read-only secondaries","B. DynamoDB Global Tables for real-time sync, Aurora Global Database for SQL databases, Route 53 geolocation routing, application state in DynamoDB (strong consistency within region, eventual across regions)","C. Batch replication every hour to secondaries","D. S3 cross-region replication with Route 53 failover"],"answer":1,"explain":"DynamoDB Global Tables replicate sub-100ms across regions. Aurora Global DB routes writes to primary, reads from any region. Route 53 geolocation directs users to nearest region. RPO = 0 achieved."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization runs hybrid cloud: on-premises VMware 10,000+ VMs, needs quick migration to AWS. VMs must remain on-premises during pilot. How to architect?","options":["A. AWS Application Migration Service (MGN) only after commitment","B. VMware Cloud on AWS: consistent hypervisor on-prem and cloud, vCenter extends to AWS, VMotion to cloud for zero-downtime migration, HCX acceleration for 100s of VMs/day migration throughput","C. Convert VMs to AMI via EC2 ImageBuilder","D. Rehost on EC2 post-migration slowly"],"answer":1,"explain":"VMware Cloud on AWS maintains VMware consistency. HCX enables rapid bulk migration. VMotion provides zero-downtime moves to pilot cloud infrastructure."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization has 50+ petabytes of data in on-premises data center needing migration to S3 data lake. Network bandwidth limited to 100 Mbps. Timeline: 6 months. What's the best approach?","options":["A. Direct Connect 10 Gbps link","B. AWS Snowball Edge 100TB devices with on-prem cluster, 60-day round-trip, parallel imports to S3, ~840 devices for 50PB transfers","C. S3 Transfer Acceleration with HTTP connections","D. Datasync with monthly snapshots"],"answer":1,"explain":"Snowball Edge 100TB devices enable physical transfer of massive data volumes. Parallel imports allow 50PB in 6-month timeline at 100Mbps. Cost-effective vs 10Gbps DX for one-time migration."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization needs a data lake serving 50 concurrent data scientists with sub-second query latency on 100TB dataset. SQL + ML workloads. Low operational overhead. What's the architecture?","options":["A. Athena with S3 Intelligent-Tiering","B. Lake Formation + Redshift Spectrum for SQL (parquet optimized format), SageMaker for ML access same Lake Formation catalog, DW nodes for sub-second latency on dimension tables, Athena for exploratory queries","C. RDS with read replicas","D. EMR Spark cluster on-demand"],"answer":1,"explain":"Redshift Spectrum queries S3 data. Redshift DW nodes provide sub-second queries on fact tables. SageMaker uses Lake Formation catalog. Athena for ad-hoc exploration. Unified metadata via Lake Formation."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization operates API platform serving 100,000+ requests/second. APIs use different patterns: REST (70%), gRPC (20%), GraphQL (10%). Need unified API management, rate limiting per customer, monetization. How to architect?","options":["A. Single API Gateway for REST","B. API Gateway for REST/GraphQL (JSON transformation), Network Load Balancer for gRPC services, API Gateway Usage Plans for rate limiting, CloudFormation templates for consistent deployment, backend services independently scaled","C. Three separate API services per protocol","D. GraphQL only, transpile others"],"answer":1,"explain":"API Gateway handles REST/GraphQL. NLB handles gRPC (binary protocol). API Gateway Usage Plans enforce rate limiting and monetization. Independent scaling per service type."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization requires complex API authentication: OAuth 2.0 for web clients, SAML for enterprise, mTLS for service-to-service, mutual TLS for partner integrations. Single API endpoint. How to architect?","options":["A. API Gateway with Lambda authorizer","B. CloudFront with Lambda@Edge for protocol switching, API Gateway with multiple authorizers (Lambda for OAuth, Cognito for SAML, request/response transform), backend mutual TLS via ALB listener rules, partner mTLS via ACM client certificates","C. Separate endpoints per auth type","D. API Gateway authorizer supporting all protocols"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda@Edge routes based on client fingerprint. API Gateway supports multiple authorizers. ALB listener rules route based on TLS cert. Enables single endpoint with protocol-specific auth."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization runs real-time event streaming: 1M events/second, 100+ consumer groups, 30-day retention, sub-second latency delivery. Consumers are AWS services and external partners via HTTPS. What's the architecture?","options":["A. Kinesis Data Streams with auto-scaling","B. Kinesis Data Streams with on-demand pricing (auto-scales to 1M EPS), Kinesis Firehose to S3 for 30-day archive, Lambda consumers for AWS services, HTTP endpoint for partners with delivery streams → Lambda transformer → HTTPS endpoint","C. Kafka on EC2 clusters","D. SNS topics with SQS queues per consumer"],"answer":1,"explain":"Kinesis on-demand auto-scales to 1M EPS. Firehose handles archive and fanout to partners. Lambda enables AWS service integration. HTTP endpoint enables external partner consumption."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization implements IoT solution: 10M connected devices sending sensor data, event-driven processing (anomalies trigger alerts <1s), device management, fleet updates. How to architect?","options":["A. IoT Core with MQTT","B. IoT Core with MQTT/HTTPS protocols, rules engine routes to services (Lambda for alerts, DynamoDB for state, S3 for archives), IoT Fleet Provisioning for scalable device onboarding, IoT Jobs for OTA firmware updates, SDK on devices, TLS cert-based auth","C. Custom Kinesis + Lambda processing","D. API Gateway endpoint per device"],"answer":1,"explain":"IoT Core manages 10M devices natively with MQTT. Rules engine enables serverless event routing. Fleet Provisioning auto-scales device onboarding. Jobs enable zero-touch firmware updates."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization needs a content delivery network for global applications. Primary concern: latency (users within 10ms of edge), security (DDoS mitigation, bot detection), custom origin logic (weighted routing to origins). How to architect?","options":["A. CloudFront with 200+ edge locations","B. CloudFront with Shield Standard (DDoS), Web ACL for bot detection + WAF, origin group (primary + secondary with auto-failover), Lambda@Edge for custom origin routing logic based on user geo/time/header, caching optimization per content type","C. Regional Application Load Balancers","D. Global Accelerator for custom routing"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront + Shield + WAF provides defense-in-depth. Origin groups enable transparent failover. Lambda@Edge enables custom routing logic at edge without touching origin. 200+ edges minimize latency."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization runs microservices (500+ services) with complex inter-service communication. Services have different SLAs (99.9%, 99.99%, 99.999%). Traffic routing must respect service SLAs. How to architect?","options":["A. Service mesh with Istio","B. AWS App Mesh with Envoy sidecars, Traffic policy per service pair (retry count, timeout, circuit breaker based on SLA), X-Ray tracing for observability, CloudWatch alarms per SLA target, auto-scaling groups per SLA tier","C. Direct service-to-service calls with client-side retry logic","D. API Gateway for all inter-service calls"],"answer":1,"explain":"App Mesh enables traffic policy per service pair respecting SLAs. Envoy sidecars provide transparent retry/timeout/circuit-breaker. X-Ray traces failures. Auto-scaling groups dedicate capacity per SLA tier."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization has petabyte-scale data warehouse. BI team runs complex aggregation queries (OLAP). Data scientists run machine learning on same data. Workloads have different resource needs and latency SLAs. How to architect?","options":["A. Single Redshift cluster with mixed workloads","B. Redshift cluster for OLAP queries with materialized views, SageMaker for ML (direct access to Redshift or S3 via Redshift Spectrum), separate compute queues for BI vs ML to prevent resource contention, RLS (Row-level Security) per user/team","C. Separate Redshift + separate EMR for ML","D. Redshift Spectrum to S3 for both workloads"],"answer":1,"explain":"Separate compute queues within single cluster prevent BI/ML resource contention. Materialized views optimize BI queries. Spectrum enables ML on broader dataset. RLS enforces data access per user."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization implements serverless application: Lambda functions, DynamoDB for storage, API Gateway for APIs, Step Functions for orchestration. Functions are latency-sensitive (P99 < 100ms). How to optimize?","options":["A. Standard Lambda with default memory","B. Lambda provisioned concurrency (eliminates cold start), VPC endpoint for DynamoDB (eliminates NAT latency), DynamoDB on-demand with DAX caching layer for sub-millisecond reads, Step Functions Express workflows for short-lived executions","C. Lambda in VPC with ENI allocation","D. Increase Lambda memory to 3008MB always"],"answer":1,"explain":"Provisioned concurrency eliminates cold starts. VPC endpoint removes NAT overhead. DAX provides sub-ms caching. Express workflows scale instantly. Achieves P99 < 100ms target."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization runs batch data processing: 100TB input, 50 billion operations, distributed computation. Jobs run overnight with <4 hour budget. How to architect for cost-efficiency?","options":["A. EC2 on-demand instances","B. AWS Batch with Spot Fleet (80% cost savings), job definition with retry logic for Spot interruptions, dependency DAG via job dependencies, S3 input/output with multipart transfer optimization","C. EMR cluster with reserved instances","D. Lambda with SQS for distributed processing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Batch + Spot Fleet saves 80% vs on-demand. Job dependencies provide DAG orchestration. Retry logic handles Spot interruptions transparently. S3 multipart optimizes throughput."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization needs to process streaming data: 100,000 events/second, complex transformations, analytics, and long-term storage. Sub-5-second end-to-end latency. How to architect?","options":["A. Kinesis Data Streams with Lambda","B. Kinesis Data Streams for ingestion with auto-scaling, Kinesis Data Analytics for real-time aggregations and anomaly detection, Kinesis Firehose to S3 for archive, Lambda for complex transformations, SNS for alerts","C. AWS Glue for batch ETL","D. Manual processing via SQS + Lambda"],"answer":1,"explain":"Kinesis handles 100K EPS natively. Analytics provides real-time aggregations. Firehose ensures durability. Lambda allows complex transformations. Architecture designed for sub-5s latency."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization runs distributed training for machine learning models across 1000+ GPUs. Models take 10 hours to train. Infrastructure spans multiple AWS regions and on-premises. How to architect?","options":["A. Single EC2 p4d instance with multi-GPU training","B. SageMaker distributed training with Horovod (inter-node communication), custom training containers, multi-region training with EFA (Elastic Fabric Adapter) for low-latency inter-node communication, on-premises training via AWS Outposts, spot instances for 70% cost savings","C. Manual distributed training orchestration with AWS Batch","D. Single on-premises cluster with cloud burst"],"answer":1,"explain":"SageMaker distributed training manages complex orchestration. EFA provides <5us latency for inter-node communication. Horovod scales gradient computation. Spot instances reduce 10-hour training cost 70%."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization requires HIPAA-compliant data processing: PII data, encryption everywhere, audit trails, access control, 6-year retention. Data includes patient medical records, genetic data. How to architect securely?","options":["A. S3 with server-side encryption, IAM policies","B. S3 with client-side encryption (asymmetric keys), S3 Object Lock for immutability, VPC endpoints to prevent internet access, CloudTrail logging all API calls, GuardDuty for intrusion detection, Macie for data classification, BareMetalInstance for HSM-based encryption key management, Config compliance rules for HIPAA standard","C. On-premises-only storage for PII","D. RDS with encryption enabled"],"answer":1,"explain":"Client-side encryption + Object Lock + VPC endpoint + GuardDuty + Macie provides HIPAA-grade security. HSM ensures cryptographic key control. Config compliance demonstrates adherence."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization implements fraud detection: transaction stream (1M/hour), real-time scoring via ML model, blocking fraudulent transactions <100ms. Models update hourly with new training data. How to architect?","options":["A. Lambda + SageMaker endpoint","B. Kinesis Data Streams ingests transactions, Lambda invokes SageMaker real-time endpoint (A/B testing with production + canary), Model registry stores models, hourly SageMaker training job updates endpoint, SNS alerts for high fraud scores, DynamoDB caches transaction history for feature engineering","C. Batch fraud detection via Spark","D. Rule-based detection without ML"],"answer":1,"explain":"Kinesis provides transaction stream. SageMaker endpoints support A/B testing (production + canary). Model registry tracks versions. Hourly jobs update models. DynamoDB enables feature engineering at scale."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization runs a SaaS platform serving 10,000+ customers with multi-tenancy. Tenants have different resource needs, SLAs, data residency. One tenant's infrastructure failure should not impact others. How to architect?","options":["A. Shared RDS with schema-per-tenant","B. RDS Aurora cluster per silo (high-touch tenants) or Shared database with row-level security (standard tenants), separate VPC per security domain (data residency), cross-account isolation for premium tenants, AWS Glue data catalog per tenant for analytics","C. Separate RDS per customer (expensive)","D. Single shared database with tenant ID column"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tiered multi-tenancy: premium = separate cluster, standard = shared with RLS. VPCs per data residency domain. Cross-account isolation for highest-security tenants."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization implements a serverless data lake: data ingestion (S3), cataloging (Glue), queries (Athena), analytics (QuickSight), security (Lake Formation). 500 users with different access levels. How to architect?","options":["A. Glue crawler → Athena queries → QuickSight dashboards","B. S3 data partitioning by date/source, Glue Crawler populates Catalog, Lake Formation permissions control access per user/group/table/column, Athena for SQL queries, QuickSight connected directly to Athena/Redshift Spectrum with RLS, Apache Iceberg for ACID transactions","C. Manual data management with SQL scripts","D. Copy to RDS for security"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lake Formation provides centralized permission management. Iceberg adds ACID transactions to S3 data lake. Athena + QuickSight directly consume catalog. RLS enforces permissions at BI tool level."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization manages hybrid infrastructure: AWS + on-premises + edge locations. Need consistent container orchestration, service mesh, observability. 500+ microservices. How to architect?","options":["A. EKS in AWS only","B. EKS Anywhere for on-premises clusters, managed EKS for AWS, AWS Service Mesh (App Mesh with Envoy proxies), X-Ray for observability, Control Plane managed centrally via AWS APIs, cross-cluster communication via Transit Gateway","C. Kubernetes manually on-premises, ECS in AWS","D. Separate management per environment"],"answer":1,"explain":"EKS Anywhere extends Kubernetes to on-premises. App Mesh provides unified service mesh. X-Ray distributed tracing across hybrid environment. TGW enables cross-cluster networking."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization requires real-time anomaly detection across all AWS resources. 500+ accounts, 10,000+ resources. Anomalies must trigger actions <5 seconds. How to architect?","options":["A. CloudWatch Alarms for each metric","B. GuardDuty for intrusion detection, Security Hub for security findings, Trusted Advisor for infrastructure anomalies, EventBridge aggregates findings from all accounts via delegated admin account, Lambda analyzes patterns via ML model, SNS alerts + Systems Manager auto-remediation, X-Ray traces anomaly causation","C. Manual log review","D. Per-account custom detection"],"answer":1,"explain":"GuardDuty + Security Hub + Trusted Advisor provide multi-signal anomaly detection. EventBridge aggregates findings. Lambda ML model analyzes patterns. Systems Manager auto-remediation triggers <5s."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization runs a video streaming platform: 100 Tbps peak throughput, global audience, 4K + HDR content. Users expect adaptive bitrate, offline download, <500ms start-up latency. How to architect?","options":["A. S3 + CloudFront with video streaming","B. AWS Elemental MediaPackage for live encoding + packaging, CloudFront global delivery with Lambda@Edge for bitrate selection, S3 for VOD with Intelligent-Tiering, DynamoDB for user state (playback position, bookmarks), offline download via Glacier Deep Archive with on-demand restoration","C. YouTube/Vimeo integration only","D. Direct video streaming from EC2"],"answer":1,"explain":"MediaPackage handles complex encoding. Lambda@Edge makes real-time bitrate decisions. CloudFront delivers to global audience. DynamoDB tracks user state. Glacier enables archival with on-demand access."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization implements complex event processing: 1M events/second, state machines, complex join operations across multiple event streams, 99.99% accuracy, exactly-once semantics. How to architect?","options":["A. Kinesis Data Streams with Lambda","B. Kinesis Data Streams, Kinesis Data Analytics for complex CEP (pattern matching, tumbling/sliding windows), Step Functions for state machine orchestration, DynamoDB for exactly-once idempotency tracking, Firehose to S3 for audit trail, X-Ray for end-to-end tracing","C. Apache Kafka custom CEP engine","D. SNS/SQS event streaming"],"answer":1,"explain":"Kinesis Analytics provides CEP language for pattern matching. Step Functions orchestrates workflows. DynamoDB idempotency ensures exactly-once. Firehose provides immutable audit trail."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization manages edge computing: 500+ edge locations with local GPU processing, cloud training, global model serving. Latency SLA: <10ms at edge. How to architect?","options":["A. Cloud-only inference via API","B. AWS IoT Greengrass for edge deployment, SageMaker Neo compilation for edge runtime optimization, local inference with <10ms latency, cloud SageMaker for retraining, fleet-wide model updates via IoT Jobs, S3 bucket for model versioning","C. Manually manage edge deployment","D. Inference via Kinesis at cloud only"],"answer":1,"explain":"IoT Greengrass enables local inference <10ms. SageMaker Neo optimizes models for edge hardware. IoT Jobs orchestrate fleet-wide updates. S3 model versioning provides rollback capability."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization implements a serverless web application: API Gateway + Lambda + DynamoDB + S3. Application growth expectation: 10x traffic in 6 months. How to architect for elastic scaling?","options":["A. Fixed Lambda memory, provisioned DynamoDB capacity","B. Lambda with provisioned concurrency (eliminates cold start), DynamoDB on-demand billing (auto-scales), CloudFront caching with TTL optimization, S3 Transfer Acceleration for global uploads, auto-scaling Lambda provisioned concurrency based on predicted load via CloudWatch anomaly detection","C. Manual capacity planning each month","D. Increase resources 2x preemptively"],"answer":1,"explain":"Provisioned concurrency + on-demand DynamoDB auto-scales elastically. CloudFront caching reduces backend load. CloudWatch anomaly detection predicts load spikes. Saves costs while handling 10x growth."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization requires a search platform: 100TB index, 1M queries/second, sub-100ms search latency, faceted search, spelling correction. How to architect?","options":["A. Elasticsearch on EC2","B. Amazon OpenSearch on dedicated hardware, UltraWarm storage for historical data, cross-cluster replication for geo-distribution, k-NN search plugin for ML-based recommendations, Query DSL with SpellChecker plugin, CloudFront in front for query result caching","C. DynamoDB query API only","D. Elasticsearch Service on provisioned capacity"],"answer":1,"explain":"OpenSearch handles 1M QPS natively. UltraWarm stores historical data cost-effectively. Cross-cluster replication provides geo-distribution. k-NN enables ML search."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization runs a multi-protocol API (REST, GraphQL, gRPC, MQTT). Clients have varying latency tolerances (10ms to 5s). Single endpoint. How to architect?","options":["A. API Gateway for all protocols","B. Network Load Balancer with TLS SNI routing, API Gateway for REST (transformed by Lambda@Edge), AppSync for GraphQL (with DataSource connectors), gRPC service via target group (ALB supports HTTP/2), MQTT via IoT Core, unified auth via Cognito + Lambda authorizer","C. Separate endpoints per protocol","D. GraphQL only with transpilers"],"answer":1,"explain":"NLB with SNI routes based on certificate/protocol. Each protocol uses native AWS service (AppSync for GraphQL, IoT Core for MQTT). Single endpoint via unified auth layer."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization implements ML Ops pipeline: continuous training (daily), model validation, A/B testing in production, model registry, automated rollback. 100+ models in production. How to architect?","options":["A. SageMaker notebooks with manual deployment","B. SageMaker Pipelines for orchestration (data validation, training, model evaluation), Model Registry for versioning, SageMaker Feature Store for feature management, Lambda for A/B testing experiment orchestration, CloudWatch alarms trigger automatic rollback if model metrics degrade, CodePipeline stages for approval gates","C. Manual ML engineer deployments","D. Single production model"],"answer":1,"explain":"Pipelines automate daily retraining. Feature Store provides consistent features. A/B testing Lambda routes traffic intelligently. Alarms trigger auto-rollback. CodePipeline approval gates ensure governance."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization implements autonomous systems: vehicles, drones, robots. Real-time processing at edge, cloud training, fleet management. 10,000+ autonomous units. How to architect?","options":["A. Cloud-only processing","B. AWS IoT Greengrass Core on vehicles for local inference, Fleet Provisioning for onboarding, AWS IoT Device Management for fleet control, cloud DynamoDB for global state (location, telemetry), SageMaker for model updates, Systems Manager for OTA deployment, S3 for sensor data archive","C. Manual per-vehicle management","D. Custom edge runtime"],"answer":1,"explain":"Greengrass Core enables local autonomous decision-making. Fleet Provisioning auto-scales to 10K units. Device Management provides control plane. SageMaker enables continuous model improvements."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization operates 5,000+ servers on-premises (VM-based). Legacy business applications, some with 20-year-old code. 2-year migration window. How to prioritize and execute?","options":["A. Rehost all servers to EC2 immediately","B. AWS Cloud Adoption Framework: assess (dependency mapping, 6Rs classification), prioritize (quick wins + business value), migrate waves (Rehost/Replatform 70%, Refactor 20%, Retire 10%), AWS MGN for rehost, AWS DMS for databases","C. Custom P2P migration tool","D. Retire legacy applications"],"answer":1,"explain":"CAF provides structured approach. 6Rs classification enables right-sizing per app. MGN handles large-scale rehost. DMS automates database migration. Phased approach minimizes risk."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization has monolithic Java application (10M lines of code, 200 engineers, 5-year release cycle). Needs to become microservices for faster innovation (2-week releases). How to migrate?","options":["A. Complete rewrite as microservices","B. Strangler Fig pattern: API facade in front of monolith, new features as microservices, gradually replace monolith components, API Gateway routes traffic, old components fall away over 2 years, no big-bang rewrite","C. Fork codebase into 20 microservices immediately","D. Keep monolith, add async workers"],"answer":1,"explain":"Strangler Fig avoids big-bang risk. API facade enables gradual replacement. Traffic routing controlled. Components retire naturally as new versions ship."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization migrates 500+ databases from on-premises Oracle (multi-terabyte) to AWS. Different apps have different downtime tolerances (0 min, 1 hr, 1 day). How to execute at scale?","options":["A. AWS DMS with full-load + CDC for all databases","B. AWS Schema Conversion Tool (auto-convert schema), DMS with continuous replication (weeks before cutover), database-specific cutover strategy (0-downtime via Aurora read replica + switchover, 1hr via reboot, 1day via batch), validation post-cutover, rollback plan per DB","C. Manual export/import with downtime","D. Lift-and-shift via Oracle Cloud VM import"],"answer":1,"explain":"SCT handles schema conversion. DMS continuous replication enables zero-downtime for 0-min apps. Flexible cutover strategy per app tolerance. Validation ensures data integrity."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization has 10,000+ traditional IT management servers (configuration, patch, deploy, monitor). Cloud-native apps emerging. Need unified management across hybrid. How to architect?","options":["A. Keep separate legacy and cloud tooling","B. AWS Systems Manager for unified management: Patch Manager for patching (hybrid agents), Session Manager for console access, Automation documents for runbooks, Ops Center for incident management, CloudWatch agent for monitoring everywhere, IAM for access control","C. Custom management tool across all servers","D. Migrate all to CloudFormation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Systems Manager bridges hybrid management. Patch Manager + Session Manager provide control. Automation documents codify runbooks. CloudWatch centralizes observability."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization migrates Windows Server workloads (Active Directory, SQL Server, Exchange, SharePoint). 200+ servers, complex interdependencies. Minimizes business disruption. How to migrate?","options":["A. Lift-and-shift all servers to EC2","B. AWS MGN (Application Migration Service) for Windows servers, AWS DataSync for file migrations, AWS Database Migration Service for SQL Server, AWS Directory Service for AD, migration in waves per application stack, parallel prod validation before cutover","C. Replatform to cloud-native (eliminate AD, use Cognito, eliminate SQL Server, use RDS/Aurora)","D. Manual server migration"],"answer":1,"explain":"MGN handles Windows rehost natively. DataSync migrates files efficiently. Database Migration Service handles SQL Server. Directory Service provides AD parity."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization has containerized microservices running on-premises (Docker, Kubernetes). Needs AWS deployment without managing Kubernetes. How to architect?","options":["A. EKS self-managed Kubernetes","B. ECS Fargate for containers (no Kubernetes), Service discovery via CloudMap, ALB for load balancing, auto-scaling via target tracking, CloudWatch logs for observability, AWS App Mesh for service mesh if needed","C. EC2-hosted containers manually","D. Kubernetes on EC2 (EKS)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Fargate eliminates Kubernetes operational burden. CloudMap provides service discovery. Auto-scaling handles demand elasticity. Fargate best for teams without Kubernetes expertise."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization runs SAP ERP system on-premises (300+ users, 2TB database, mission-critical 24/7). Migration must have <5 min RTO, zero data loss. How to migrate?","options":["A. Backup/restore to EC2","B. AWS Application Migration Service (MGN) for compute + AWS Database Migration Service (DMS) continuous replication for SAP database, parallel environment testing, Route 53 health check triggers automatic DNS failover to AWS, rollback procedure pre-tested, cutover during maintenance window <5 min","C. SAP HANA on AWS with data import","D. Keep on-premises, use AWS for disaster recovery only"],"answer":1,"explain":"MGN replicates SAP compute. DMS continuous replication ensures database consistency. Route 53 health check triggers automatic failover. Pre-tested rollback ensures safety."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization has Salesforce on-premises customization layer (1M lines of Apex code, custom integrations). Needs to run on Salesforce cloud. How to migrate?","options":["A. Salesforce SFDC API only","B. Salesforce Functions (serverless compute on SFDC platform), AWS Lambda for complex logic (via Salesforce outbound events), Salesforce DataCloud for unified data, AWS integration via VPC endpoints, Apex code gradually refactored to Functions","C. Custom Java app replicating Salesforce","D. Dual-run on-premises + SFDC"],"answer":1,"explain":"Salesforce Functions runs serverless in SFDC. Lambda handles complex AWS-specific logic. DataCloud provides unified view. Gradual refactoring avoids big-bang risk."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization operates data warehouse (Teradata, 100TB, 2,000+ reports). Migration to AWS required. Some reports run nightly, some real-time dashboards. How to migrate?","options":["A. Migrate directly to Redshift","B. AWS Glue ETL scripts replace Teradata ETL, Redshift DW for OLAP (nightly reports), Amazon QuickSight for real-time dashboards (Athena + S3 for ad-hoc), S3 acts as data lake, graduated license cost from Teradata","C. Keep Teradata, cloud-based reporting only","D. Snowflake migration instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"Glue provides ETL automation. Redshift handles large OLAP workloads. Athena enables ad-hoc queries. QuickSight provides BI. Gradual migration by workload."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization operates mainframe legacy billing system (CICS, 40 years old). Needs cloud migration while supporting legacy interfaces (batch files, async messages, FTP). How to architect?","options":["A. Rewrite entirely in Java","B. AWS Mainframe Modernization: use Automated migration tool to convert COBOL to Java, containerize into ECS, maintain legacy interfaces via API Gateway + Lambda transformers, API Gateway + ALB for FTP protocol support via custom handlers","C. Run mainframe in AWS via migration license","D. Keep mainframe, add cloud layer"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Mainframe Modernization auto-converts COBOL. ECS containers replace mainframe compute. Lambda transformers bridge legacy interfaces. Maintains interfaces while modernizing internally."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization has legacy LAMP stack websites (PHP, MySQL, Apache). 50+ websites, mix of in-house and third-party code. How to migrate efficiently?","options":["A. Lift-and-shift each website to EC2","B. Elastic Beanstalk for PHP apps (auto-scaling, zero-downtime deployments), RDS Aurora MySQL for databases, Route 53 routing per app, S3 + CloudFront for static assets, DMS for MySQL migration, database parameter store for per-app config","C. Rewrite all PHP as Lambda","D. Migrate one website at a time manually"],"answer":1,"explain":"Beanstalk handles PHP scaling + deployments. RDS Aurora provides MySQL compatibility. Route 53 enables per-app routing. S3+CloudFront optimizes static content. DMS automates database migration."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization operates NoSQL database (MongoDB) on-premises with 500GB data, 10K documents/sec throughput. Needs AWS migration. Some operations require transactions (ACID). How to migrate?","options":["A. DynamoDB directly","B. AWS Database Migration Service (DMS) for MongoDB → DynamoDB (with transformation), or MongoDB Atlas on AWS for MongoDB-compatible API, DynamoDB global tables for multi-region, provisioned capacity tuned to 10K DPS, conditional writes for transaction simulation","C. Keep MongoDB on-premises, add cloud layer","D. Migrate to RDS"],"answer":1,"explain":"DMS migrates MongoDB to DynamoDB with transformations. Global tables provide multi-region consistency. Conditional writes simulate transactions. Atlas provides MongoDB compatibility if needed."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization runs Apache Spark analytics jobs on-premises cluster (500 nodes, 10TB working set). Jobs run nightly (6 hour batches). How to migrate to AWS cost-effectively?","options":["A. EC2 Spot instances for cluster","B. AWS Glue (serverless Spark) replaces cluster, auto-scales per job, scales 0→500 cores elastically, S3 acts as data lake, provisioned capacity for baseline, Spot for variable capacity, saves 70% vs on-prem cluster amortization","C. EMR cluster for Spark jobs","D. Lambda for ETL instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"Glue serverless eliminates cluster management. Auto-scaling to 500 cores for batch. S3 replaces HDFS. Spot integration saves 70%. Scales to zero between batches."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization has complex on-premises network (site-to-site VPN, ExpressRoute, multiple data centers). Cloud migration requires hybrid networking. How to design migration?","options":["A. Single AWS region via single VPN","B. AWS Direct Connect for high-bandwidth hybrid connectivity, AWS Transit Gateway for multi-region + on-premises hub-spoke routing, AWS VPN as backup, gradual data center decommission with traffic shift via Route 53, hybrid DNS (Route 53 resolver endpoints)","C. Keep separate networks indefinitely","D. Cut-over all traffic simultaneously"],"answer":1,"explain":"Direct Connect provides reliable hybrid backbone. TGW enables hub-spoke routing. VPN provides backup. Route 53 traffic shift enables gradual cutover. Hybrid DNS bridges naming."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization runs multi-tier application (web, app, database tier) on-premises. Each tier has independent scaling requirements. Cloud migration must minimize code changes. How to architect?","options":["A. Move all tiers to EC2 with same architecture","B. AWS Elastic Beanstalk for web tier (auto-scaling), ECS for app tier (containerized), RDS for database tier, Application Load Balancer for tier communication, auto-scaling groups per tier based on independent metrics, minimal code changes (add CloudWatch metrics emission)","C. Lambda for all tiers (refactor needed)","D. Monolithic EC2 application"],"answer":1,"explain":"Beanstalk + ECS + RDS preserves multi-tier architecture. ALB coordinates tier communication. Independent auto-scaling groups optimize costs. Minimal code changes enable fast migration."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization has geographically distributed offices with local on-premises servers, each with local storage. Needs consolidation to AWS. Local latency requirements must be met. How to migrate?","options":["A. Single AWS region, all users remote access","B. AWS Local Zones co-located with major offices (LA, NYC, Dallas) for <1ms latency, parent region for non-latency-sensitive workloads, AWS Direct Connect from offices to parent regions, S3 multi-region replication for data residency, Route 53 latency-based routing","C. Keep local servers indefinitely","D. Regional consolidation to 3 offices"],"answer":1,"explain":"Local Zones provide <1ms latency for latency-sensitive workloads. Parent region for shared services. Direct Connect backbone. Multi-region S3 ensures data residency."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization has legacy vendor software with license tied to on-premises MAC address/hardware. Cloud migration breaks licensing. How to maintain compliance?","options":["A. Purchase new cloud licenses (high cost)","B. AWS License Manager for license tracking, vendor negotiation for license portability, MAC address spoofing via EC2 user data (if vendor allows), license affinity via placement groups to ensure same hardware allocation, AWS licensing marketplace for vendor solutions","C. Keep software on-premises forever","D. Virtualize on-premises, license per VM"],"answer":1,"explain":"License Manager tracks usage for compliance. Negotiation explores vendor flexibility. EC2 user data enables MAC spoofing. Placement groups ensure hardware affinity. Marketplace may have pre-licensed solutions."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization operates Microsoft Exchange (email/calendar) on-premises (50,000 users). Migration to O365 needed without business disruption. How to migrate?","options":["A. Cutover all mailboxes simultaneously","B. AWS DataSync for hybrid connectivity setup, Microsoft Hybrid Agent enables gradual migration (batches of users per week), co-existence period allows client updates, Route 53 alias for mailbox routing, post-migration mail flow rules redirect legacy systems, mailbox verification per wave before proceeding","C. Keep Exchange on-premises","D. AWS WorkMail instead of O365"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hybrid Agent enables staged migration. DataSync provides network bridge. Co-existence period allows client updates. Per-wave verification ensures reliability. No big-bang cutover risk."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization runs complex build/test/release pipeline for software product (1000+ daily builds, 50+ AWS accounts for test environments). Pipeline manually orchestrated. Needs AWS-native automation. How to architect?","options":["A. Jenkins on EC2","B. AWS CodePipeline orchestrates stages, CodeBuild for compilation+testing (cross-account roles for 50 test accounts), CodeDeploy for release, S3 for artifacts, ECR for container images, CloudFormation for test environment provisioning/teardown, per-developer cost tracking","C. GitLab CI/CD on EC2","D. Manual stage execution"],"answer":1,"explain":"CodePipeline orchestrates multi-stage build. CodeBuild scales test parallelization. Cross-account roles enable 50 test environments. CloudFormation auto-provisions/destroys test env. Cost-optimized via teardown."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization has Kubernetes on-premises (200+ apps, 500 pods). Migration to AWS required. Some apps need strict latency (<5ms), others batch processing. How to migrate?","options":["A. EKS self-managed (full Kubernetes)","B. EKS (for latency-sensitive workloads) + Fargate/EC2 mix (batch workloads), Karpenter for cost-optimized auto-scaling, cluster autoscaler for latency-sensitive nodes (dedicated capacity reservations), Helm for app deployment consistency, cost tracking via tags, no application code changes","C. ECS instead of EKS","D. Kubernetes on EC2 (unmanaged)"],"answer":1,"explain":"EKS maintains Kubernetes consistency. Karpenter optimizes batch workload costs via Spot. Dedicated capacity reservations ensure latency SLA. Helm manages complexity. No app code changes needed."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization operates Time-Series Database (InfluxDB) for monitoring (metrics from 100K sources, 1B metrics/day). Needs cloud migration. 6-month lookback required. How to migrate efficiently?","options":["A. AWS CloudWatch only (limited metrics)","B. Amazon Timestream for managed time-series, AWS DMS for historical data migration (bulk load + incremental replication), CloudWatch agent for metric collection, S3 for 6-month archive via Intelligent-Tiering, Grafana datasource for InfluxDB compatibility via Timestream","C. Keep InfluxDB on EC2","D. Migrate to Prometheus"],"answer":1,"explain":"Timestream handles 1B metrics/day natively. DMS migrates InfluxDB data. Intelligent-Tiering stores 6-month archive cost-effectively. Grafana integration maintains UI consistency."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization has 100+ third-party SaaS integrations (Salesforce, ServiceNow, HubSpot, etc.) in legacy system. Cloud migration requires maintaining integrations. How to architect?","options":["A. AWS Service Catalog for SaaS integrations","B. AWS AppFlow for low-code SaaS integration, EventBridge for event-driven SaaS workflows, Lambda for custom transformation logic, Systems Manager Parameter Store for SaaS credentials, CloudWatch monitoring for integration health, automated error correction via Lambda","C. Custom API layer per SaaS","D. Maintain legacy system indefinitely"],"answer":1,"explain":"AppFlow provides low-code SaaS connectors. EventBridge enables event-driven integrations. Lambda handles complex transformations. Parameter Store secures credentials. Automated monitoring + correction."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization runs Oracle Identity Management (OIM) on-premises for 50,000+ employees. Cloud migration requires employee/contractor identity management with minimal operational overhead. How to migrate?","options":["A. AWS IAM for all users (per-person IAM user)","B. AWS Cognito with SAML federation to existing OIM (gradual migration), AWS Directory Service for hybrid AD, Systems Manager for federated device management, AWS IAM Identity Center for permission set management, eventually retire OIM","C. Keep OIM forever, cloud-only apps use separate identity","D. Lightweight LDAP on EC2"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cognito enables SAML federation to OIM during migration. Directory Service maintains AD parity. Identity Center provides permission management at scale. Gradual OIM retirement minimizes risk."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization has legacy CRM (custom-built, 500 concurrent users, 10-year-old codebase). Needs migration to cloud. Codebase in COBOL, uses proprietary database. How to migrate?","options":["A. Complete rewrite as modern web app","B. AWS Mainframe Modernization: convert COBOL to Java, AWS DMS for proprietary database (schema conversion first), containerize via ECS, Lambda for API layer, gradual feature migration to modern tech stack, maintain COBOL where cost-prohibitive to convert","C. Run on mainframe emulation in AWS","D. Retire legacy CRM, use cloud SaaS"],"answer":1,"explain":"Mainframe Modernization auto-converts COBOL. DMS handles database migration. Containers isolate legacy services. Lambda bridges APIs. Selective modernization balances cost/benefit."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization operates PeopleSoft HCM (HR system) on-premises serving 30,000 employees. Needs AWS migration with zero HR system downtime (24/7 system). How to execute?","options":["A. PeopleSoft on EC2, RDS for database, parallel prod for testing","B. AWS Application Migration Service (MGN) for PeopleSoft application server, AWS Database Migration Service (continuous replication) for PeopleSoft database, multi-AZ RDS for high availability, Route 53 health check triggers automatic failover, HR team validates end-to-end before cutover, parallel production environment for testing (2 weeks)","C. Cloud-based Workday instead of PeopleSoft","D. Slow phased cutover"],"answer":1,"explain":"MGN + DMS enables parallel validation. Multi-AZ RDS ensures availability. Route 53 health check provides automatic failover. Two-week testing window minimizes cutover risk."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization runs custom JBoss application server cluster (20 servers, stateful sessions, performance-sensitive). Cloud migration requires <5% performance regression. How to migrate?","options":["A. JBoss on EC2 with ASG","B. AWS Elastic Beanstalk for Java workloads (handles JBoss), session replication via ElastiCache Redis (replaces in-app clustering), Network Load Balancer for sticky sessions, performance testing pre/post-migration (load test same profile), rollback plan with on-premises JBoss as backup","C. Refactor to Lambda","D. Keep JBoss on-premises"],"answer":1,"explain":"Beanstalk handles JBoss complexity. ElastiCache Redis replaces in-app session clustering. NLB sticky sessions ensure affinity. Load test validation proves <5% regression. Rollback plan ensures safety."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization has financial trading application (latency-sensitive, microsecond precision). Runs on custom-optimized on-premises hardware. Migration to cloud must preserve latency (<1ms tail latency). How to architect?","options":["A. Standard EC2 in AWS","B. AWS Graviton3 instances (custom silicone) for latency optimization, placement groups for low inter-node latency, dedicated capacity reservations for guaranteed hardware allocation, Enhanced Networking (SR-IOV) for <1µs network latency, nitro system for lower overhead, co-location in AWS Local Zone if available","C. Keep on-premises indefinitely","D. Hybrid model with cloud burst"],"answer":1,"explain":"Graviton3 provides custom silicon for latency. Placement groups + dedicated capacity ensure consistent hardware. Enhanced Networking + Nitro system reduce kernel overhead. Local Zones offer <1ms to edge."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization has multi-region on-premises disaster recovery setup (active-active across 2 DCs). Cloud migration must maintain multi-region active-active. How to architect?","options":["A. Single AWS region active, multi-region passive","B. Multi-region active-active: DynamoDB Global Tables for data consistency (RPO = 0), Aurora Global Database for SQL databases (cross-region read replicas), Route 53 geolocation routing for active-active traffic, on-premises DC decommissioned post-validation, TGW inter-region peering during transition","C. Keep on-premises dual DCs","D. Cloud primary, on-premises standby only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Global Tables achieve active-active with RPO=0. Aurora Global DB provides cross-region consistency. Route 53 geolocation routing enables active-active traffic distribution."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization operates DataStax Cassandra cluster (500 nodes, multi-region, petabyte-scale). Cloud migration required. How to migrate to AWS with zero downtime?","options":["A. AWS RDS Cassandra","B. Amazon Keyspaces (Cassandra-compatible managed service), AWS DMS for data migration (bulk load + incremental sync), dual-write pattern during transition (write to on-prem + Keyspaces), gradual route traffic shift via application config, on-premises cluster decommissioning after verification","C. Cassandra on EC2","D. Migrate to DynamoDB only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Keyspaces provides Cassandra API compatibility. DMS handles bulk + incremental migration. Dual-write pattern ensures consistency during transition. Gradual traffic shift minimizes risk."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization has Splunk on-premises (2TB/day log ingestion, 30TB index, 500+ apps feeding logs). Cloud migration required with cost reduction goal. How to architect?","options":["A. Splunk Cloud SaaS","B. AWS CloudWatch Logs (unified destination for all log sources), S3 for long-term archive via log lifecycle policies (Intelligent-Tiering), Athena for ad-hoc log queries, QuickSight for visualization, anomaly detection via CloudWatch alarms + X-Ray, gradual application rerouting from Splunk → CloudWatch Logs","C. Splunk on EC2 in AWS","D. Keep Splunk on-premises, supplement with CloudWatch"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudWatch Logs replaces Splunk. S3 Intelligent-Tiering archives economically. Athena enables ad-hoc queries. QuickSight provides visualization. 50%+ cost reduction vs Splunk."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization runs custom Apache web server + Perl/CGI application (20-year-old, 5M lines). Low business value to refactor. Cloud migration must enable end-of-life. How to maximize cloud benefit while minimizing refactoring?","options":["A. Refactor to modern stack","B. AWS Elastic Beanstalk for legacy web applications, minimal code changes (Apache + Perl runtime), auto-scaling handles variable load, CloudWatch monitoring for health, API Gateway facade for new microservices (strangler fig), gradual retirement of legacy app components","C. Keep on-premises forever","D. EC2 lift-and-shift only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Beanstalk handles Apache+Perl natively with minimal changes. Auto-scaling optimizes costs. Strangler fig enables gradual modernization. End-of-life planning begins immediately."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization spends $50M/year on AWS across 250 accounts. Finance needs detailed cost allocation per department, project, environment. CFO requires quarterly TCO analysis and cost trend forecasting. How to architect for cost governance?","options":["A. Cost Explorer grouping by tag","B. AWS Cost and Usage Report (detailed CUR) to S3, QuickSight for self-service analytics, Compute Optimizer for rightsizing recommendations (saves ~20%), cost anomaly detection for spend spikes, quarterly forecast via ML model on historical trends, chargeback automation via ServiceNow integration","C. Billing alerts with manual analysis","D. Cost per account via Organizations"],"answer":1,"explain":"CUR provides raw data for custom analysis. QuickSight enables self-service. Compute Optimizer saves 20%. Anomaly detection prevents surprise bills. ML forecasting guides quarterly planning."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization runs analytics on petabyte-scale data. Tableau, Looker, Power BI all used by different departments. Cost optimization critical given query volume. How to optimize analytics costs?","options":["A. Single Redshift cluster for all BI tools","B. Redshift for dashboard cache (materialized views, reserved capacity), Athena with S3 Intelligent-Tiering for ad-hoc queries (10-50% cost savings), QuickSight SPICE cache for Tableau/Looker federated queries, auto-refresh schedules for dashboards, per-tool cost tracking via tags","C. Separate cloud data warehouse per tool","D. On-premises data warehouse"],"answer":1,"explain":"Redshift caches hot data (dashboards). Athena queries cold data cost-effectively. Intelligent-Tiering saves storage costs. SPICE cache minimizes query volume. Per-tool tracking enables optimization."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization has 50,000+ EC2 instances across 150 accounts (dev, test, prod). Average utilization 20%. Compute costs $100M/year. How to optimize to $70M (30% savings)?","options":["A. Reserved Instances for all instances","B. Compute Optimizer for right-sizing recommendations (5-10% savings), Savings Plans (1-3 year) for predictable workloads (10-15% savings), Spot Instances for fault-tolerant workloads (50-70% savings), Scheduled shutdown for dev/test outside business hours (10-20% savings), total potential: 30% or more","C. Migrate to smaller instance types","D. Off-premises (no savings)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Compute Optimizer identifies oversized instances. Savings Plans optimize reserved capacity. Spot exploits fault-tolerant workloads. Scheduled shutdown targets non-production. Combined: 30%+ savings possible."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization operates a SaaS platform with 100,000+ customers on AWS. Per-customer marginal cost must be calculated for unit economics and pricing. How to architect cost tracking?","options":["A. CloudWatch metrics per customer","B. AWS Billing Conductor for custom cost allocation models per customer, CUR normalized pricing, per-customer compute + storage + data transfer + third-party costs calculated deterministically, chargeback via Stripe integration for customer billing automation, per-tier SLA cost targets (e.g., $2/customer max)","C. Manual cost allocation spreadsheet","D. Cost proportional to usage only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Billing Conductor enables custom cost allocation. CUR provides normalized pricing. Deterministic calculation enables per-customer tracking. Stripe integration automates billing."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization hosts 500+ websites on AWS (shared hosting model). Different websites have different traffic patterns (seasonal peaks, event-driven spikes). Fixed costs dominate. How to optimize?","options":["A. Right-size each website individually","B. Shared Application Load Balancer across all websites (cost amortized), CloudFront for cache hit rate optimization (reduces origin load 90%), Lambda@Edge for request transformation (eliminates origin processing), auto-scaling groups shared per region, cost per website tracked via ALB access logs + CloudWatch metrics","C. Separate ALB per website","D. On-premises hosting"],"answer":1,"explain":"Shared ALB amortizes load-balancing cost. CloudFront cache hits reduce origin load 90%. Lambda@Edge moves processing to edge. Auto-scaling groups shared across many websites. Cost per website ~80% lower."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization runs batch ETL jobs: 1000+ daily Spark jobs, each running 5-60 minutes. Combined 10,000 core-hours daily. Job failures are recoverable, latency not critical. How to optimize compute costs?","options":["A. Reserved on-demand capacity","B. AWS Glue with Spot Instances (60-70% cost savings), job bookmarks for incremental processing (reduce re-runs), max capacity auto-scaling to prevent queue buildup, job retry with exponential backoff for Spot interruptions, cost per core-hour: $0.20 (Spot) vs $1.20 (on-demand)","C. EMR cluster always-on","D. Kubernetes on EC2 on-demand"],"answer":1,"explain":"Glue Spot integration saves 60-70% on compute. Job bookmarks reduce re-runs. Auto-scaling prevents queue buildup. Retry logic handles Spot interruptions. Per-job cost tracking enables optimization."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization stores 10PB of data in S3: hot (1%), warm (10%), cold (89%). Access patterns: hot accessed daily, warm monthly, cold rarely accessed. Annual S3 cost: $500K. How to reduce to $100K?","options":["A. Compress all data","B. S3 Intelligent-Tiering for automatic tiering based on access (saves ~60% vs standard), Glacier Deep Archive for cold data (saves ~95% on cold data), S3 batch operations for bulk lifecycle transitions, archive non-accessed data after 60 days, estimated: $100K","C. Delete old data","D. On-premises storage"],"answer":1,"explain":"Intelligent-Tiering auto-tiers based on access frequency. Deep Archive saves 95% on cold data. Batch operations automate lifecycle. Targeted tiering saves $400K/year on 10PB."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization runs Lambda functions: 10B invocations/month, avg 512MB, avg 100ms duration. Cost: $150K/month. Workload is idempotent and latency-tolerant. How to reduce costs?","options":["A. Reduce memory to 128MB (slows code, increases duration)","B. Lambda Provisioned Concurrency for baseline (reduces cold starts, consistent duration), Reserved Concurrency for capacity guarantees, Compute Savings Plans (1-year contract, 17% discount), cost optimization: move to Lambda instead of idle EC2 might save 60%","C. Migrate to EC2 (always-on cost)","D. Keep current"],"answer":1,"explain":"Provisioned Concurrency eliminates cold start overhead. Compute Savings Plans provide contractual discount. Reserved Concurrency ensures capacity. Combined: 20-30% savings on Lambda."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization runs RDS: 50 databases, mix of MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQL Server. Combined: 500 GB storage, 50K IOPS. Annual RDS cost: $800K. How to optimize?","options":["A. Downsize all instances","B. AWS Graviton-based RDS instances (saves 20%), Reserved Instances (1-year, saves 30%), Aurora MySQL/PostgreSQL migration (saves 40% vs RDS, better scaling), consolidate databases (eliminate standalone instances), estimated annual: $320K (60% savings)","C. Self-managed RDS on EC2 (complex)","D. On-premises"],"answer":1,"explain":"Graviton instances reduce compute costs 20%. Reserved Instances provide contractual discount. Aurora is 40% cheaper than RDS. Consolidation eliminates overhead. 60% savings achievable."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization has multi-account environment with 200+ AWS accounts. Consolidated billing exists but cost attribution is manual. Finance needs per-account chargeback and per-cost-center accountability. How to automate?","options":["A. Cost Explorer tags per account","B. AWS Cost Allocation Tags enforced via SCPs, CUR to S3 partitioned by account+tag, Lambda cost engine allocates multi-account shared services (TGW, shared NAT, shared RDS), automated monthly chargeback email per cost center via Systems Manager + SNS, cost variance analysis via Redshift","C. Manual spreadsheet per month","D. Per-account consolidated billing only"],"answer":1,"explain":"CUR provides detailed data for allocation. Lambda engine handles shared service allocation. SCP enforcement ensures tagging. Automated chargeback eliminates manual work. Variance analysis enables optimization."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization has data center with 1000+ physical servers. Cloud migration in progress (2-year timeline). Current on-premises: $20M/year (amortized hardware, power, cooling, staff). Cloud: $18M/year projected. How to justify additional $2M hybrid costs during migration?","options":["A. Accelerate migration (too risky)","B. Hybrid cost analysis: overlap period 24 months of dual infrastructure is planned cost, cost-benefit: reduced operational risk (on-premises stability for 24m), reduced training risk (gradual skill transition), avoid stranded assets, cost per month saved post-migration: $1.7M (60% savings baseline), 18-month payback on dual costs","C. Keep on-premises only, no cloud","D. Cloud-only, rapid migration"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hybrid overlap justified by risk mitigation. Operational stability enables gradual transition. Training time for staff. Post-migration savings ($1.7M/month) justify 18-month investment. TCO still favorable."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization plans to migrate database workload from on-premises (500GB, 10K IOPS, multi-region DR). Current cost: $2M/year. Cloud options: RDS ($1.2M), Aurora ($700K), DynamoDB ($1.5M). How to choose?","options":["A. Cheapest = DynamoDB","B. TCO analysis: RDS has lowest support cost (AWS manages), but licensing for SQL Server is extra; Aurora is 40% cheaper than RDS, supports MySQL/PostgreSQL only; DynamoDB requires code refactoring (hidden cost); recommendation: Aurora if schema supports, else RDS with 1-year RI, both << on-prem cost","C. Keep on-premises","D. Dual-cloud for cost arbitrage"],"answer":1,"explain":"TCO considers total cost not just database. RDS requires licensing. Aurora cheaper but less flexible. DynamoDB refactoring cost high. RDS+RI best value for SQL Server."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization runs 24/7 production systems. Some regions are active (business hours), others have variable load (global spikes). How to optimize with right-sizing and Reserved Instances?","options":["A. Reserve peak capacity everywhere","B. Regional RI strategy: business-hours regions (Americas, EU) reserve 80% of peak; Asia regions reserve 40% (lower utilization); On-Demand for burst, Spot for non-critical; savings: 40-50% vs all On-Demand, flexibility for sudden traffic shifts","C. All On-Demand, pay premium","D. All Reserved, pay for unused capacity"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tiered RI strategy matches regional utilization patterns. Spot handles burst cost-effectively. Flexibility for traffic shifts. 40-50% savings vs all On-Demand, better than all Reserved."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization has shared infrastructure services (NAT Gateway, TGW, shared RDS). 15 departments use these shared services. Finance needs per-department cost allocation. How to fairly distribute $5M annual shared service cost?","options":["A. Equal split per department","B. Cost allocation engine: NAT usage = based on outbound bytes (via CloudWatch metrics), TGW usage = based on TGW attachment hours, RDS usage = based on query time + storage, per-department allocation via cost tags, actual-cost chargeback ensures fairness and incentivizes optimization","C. Charge only departments using services (unfair)","D. No chargeback, free shared services (no incentive)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Usage-based allocation fair and incentive-aligned. CloudWatch metrics provide accurate usage tracking. Cost tags enable automation. Departments optimize based on actual usage costs."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization purchases Reserved Instances: 500x m5.xlarge for 1-year in January. Business changes: only 300 needed by September (300 idle). How to minimize loss?","options":["A. Terminate unused instances (still pay)","B. AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace: sell 200 unused RIs for ~70% of purchase price ($20K loss on $28K cost), use Compute Optimizer to right-size, consider capacity scheduler to power-on/off during business hours instead of terminating, estimated total loss: 15% vs 40% if held","C. Keep unused indefinitely","D. Buy all capacity as On-Demand (more expensive)"],"answer":1,"explain":"RI Marketplace enables liquidation at ~70% value. Scheduler reduces wasted capacity cost. Right-sizing prevents future overprovisioning. Total loss 15% vs 40% if doing nothing."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization implements AWS Cost Anomaly Detection. Monthly alerts: 20% of departments have anomalies (usually false positives). CFO wants actionable alerts only. How to improve signal-to-noise ratio?","options":["A. Increase threshold to 50% (misses real anomalies)","B. Machine learning models per department (not all departments same growth patterns), alert only if anomaly + manual rule matches (e.g., storage spike + no known bulk import), Slack integration for team acknowledgement before escalation, cost: same, impact: 80% fewer false positives","C. Disable anomaly detection","D. Manual review all alerts"],"answer":1,"explain":"ML models per department capture unique growth patterns. Manual rules filter false positives. Slack acknowledgement ensures team awareness. Signal-to-noise improves 80%, actionable alerts increase."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization runs serverless: Lambda, API Gateway, DynamoDB, S3. Monthly cost: $500K. 70% Lambda, 20% data storage, 10% APIs. How to achieve 30% cost reduction?","options":["A. Reduce Lambda memory (slows code)","B. Lambda optimization: Provisioned Concurrency for baseline ($150/month vs cold start overhead 50% faster, $100K savings), Right-sizing memory per function via CloudWatch profiling ($50K savings), DynamoDB: Spot instances via DynamoDB on-demand auto-scaling ($75K savings), S3 Intelligent-Tiering ($25K savings), estimated: $250K remaining (50% savings)","C. Migrate to EC2 (less efficient)","D. Accept high costs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Provisioned Concurrency eliminates overhead. Right-sizing per function. DynamoDB on-demand auto-scaling. S3 Intelligent-Tiering. Combined: 50% savings on Lambda-heavy workloads."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization has SaaS platform with usage-based pricing. Cost per unit: $0.05. Billing to customers: $0.10 per unit. Margin: 100%. As scale increases to 10B units/month, COGS per unit increasing (AWS costs rising). Why?","options":["A. AWS raising prices","B. Data transfer costs (egress from EC2/RDS to customer), inter-AZ traffic, API calls per unit (cost per API call adds up), queue depth increasing (higher storage costs), no per-unit cost optimization. Solution: reduce data transfer (CloudFront), use on-demand compute (auto-scaling down during off-peak), cache aggressively, optimize API call efficiency","C. Competition","D. Natural economy of scale"],"answer":1,"explain":"Data transfer, inter-AZ traffic, API calls accumulate. At scale, per-unit optimization critical. CloudFront reduces egress. On-demand compute eliminates idle cost. Aggressive caching cuts API calls."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization has AWS Reserved Instance portfolio: 2000x instances purchased over 3 years. Different regions, different types. Instance families evolving (m5 → m6i → m7i). How to optimize RI portfolio?","options":["A. Keep all RIs, renew at expiration","B. RI Utilization Report monthly, convert Graviton (20% cheaper), sell under-utilized RIs via RI Marketplace, purchase 1-year RIs (more flexibility than 3-year), use Compute Optimizer recommendations for family transitions, estimated: 15% savings on existing RI spend","C. Buy all instances as On-Demand (higher cost)","D. All Spot instances (unreliable)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Compute Optimizer recommends family transitions. RI Marketplace enables rebalancing. 1-year contracts provide flexibility. Graviton instances cheaper. Portfolio optimization saves 15% on RI costs."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization has regional data lake: 100TB in us-east-1, 50TB in eu-west-1. Both store full copies. Data transfer between regions during queries costs $500K/year. How to reduce without losing regional isolation?","options":["A. Delete regional copies (non-compliant)","B. S3 Intelligent-Tiering with cross-region replication for frequently accessed data only, on-demand restoration for less-used data, S3 SELECT for partial retrieval (reduce transfer volume), data residency: query locally to avoid transfer (push compute to data), estimated: $100K (80% savings on transfer)","C. Keep separate copies","D. On-premises regional cache"],"answer":1,"explain":"Intelligent-Tiering reduces replicated volume. S3 SELECT reduces transfer. Query locally avoids transfer. On-demand restoration for rare queries. 80% transfer cost savings achievable."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization runs multi-region active-active: application data in DynamoDB Global Tables. Replication across 3 regions costs $500K/year (per-region write costs). How to optimize?","options":["A. Keep all replicas (business needs)","B. Global Tables write-once region (primary only full replicas), read-only replicas via cross-region DynamoDB streams (no write costs), Route 53 health check redirects writes to primary, cross-region read cost 50% lower than write, estimated: $250K (50% savings on replication)","C. Single region only (no multi-region)","D. Accept high costs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Write-once strategy (single primary, read-only replicas) saves replication costs. DynamoDB streams provide read-only access cheaper. Route 53 ensures write traffic to primary. 50% savings achievable."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization implements cloud financial operations (FinOps). Current cost: $200M/year. Goal: reduce to $150M (25% savings) over 18 months. How to structure FinOps program?","options":["A. Cost cutting across all services","B. FinOps framework: Inform (CUR dashboards), Optimize (right-sizing + Spot), Operate (auto-scaling + scheduling), measure value delivered per $1 spent, assign cost owners per department, quarterly business reviews of cost vs revenue, estimated: $50M savings via right-sizing (20%), Spot/scheduling (3%), organizational efficiency (2%)","C. One-time cost reduction initiative","D. Hire cost consultants only"],"answer":1,"explain":"FinOps framework provides structure. CUR + dashboards enable visibility. Right-sizing + Spot + scheduling provide levers. Cost owners ensure accountability. 25% savings achievable over 18 months."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization runs nonprofit data processing on AWS (free tier exhausted). Budget: $100K/year. Cost per transaction: $0.001 (on-demand pricing). How to operate sustainably within budget?","options":["A. Reduce processing volume","B. Nonprofit program: AWS Activate grants ($10K + tech support), Spot Instances for non-latency-critical work (50% savings), Compute Savings Plans (17% discount), Lambda for occasional work (no idle cost), transition to serverless where possible, re-estimate per-transaction cost: $0.0003, annual cost estimate: $30K (3x volume within budget)","C. Accept budget overages","D. Migrate to on-premises"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Activate provides grants. Spot + Savings Plans reduce costs 50%+. Serverless eliminates idle cost. Per-transaction cost drops 3x. Enables 3x scale within budget."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization is startup with AWS bill doubling quarterly (growth!). Current: $5K/month. In 6 months: $20K/month projected. How to prevent bill shock and ensure cost efficiency during growth?","options":["A. Stop tracking costs (ignore problem)","B. Cost guardrails: budgets with alerts at 50%, 75%, 90%, right-size weekly via Compute Optimizer, auto-scaling groups to prevent over-provisioning, Spot for non-critical (50% savings), cost per unit tracked to ensure margin (revenue / AWS cost ratio), estimated: $12K/month in 6 months vs $20K (40% efficiency improvement)","C. Raise prices immediately","D. Migrate to cheaper cloud"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cost guardrails provide early warnings. Weekly optimization prevents drift. Spot + auto-scaling reduce bill. Cost per unit tracking ensures unit economics. Margins protected during growth."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization implements automated cost governance: SCPs prevent expensive services (multi-region replication, 3-AZ deployments, 24/7 on-demand). Teams use cheaper alternatives. Cost reduction: $10M/year, but some services legitimately need expensive deployment. How to enable exceptions safely?","options":["A. Open SCPs completely (no governance)","B. SCP with exceptions list (per-account, per-service), approval process for exceptions (cost owner + finance), tagged resources indicate \"approved expensive\", quarterly review of exception list for consolidation, automated enforcement for non-exceptions, estimated: $8M savings (still 80% of benefit) with safety valve","C. No SCP, trust teams","D. SCP mandatory, no exceptions"],"answer":1,"explain":"Exceptions list enables legitimate multi-region/HA deployments. Approval gate ensures cost-benefit analysis. Tagging enables tracking. Quarterly review consolidates exceptions. 80% savings with safety."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 300-account organization needs to prevent accidental deletion of critical resources (RDS production, DynamoDB tables with customer data). SCPs can't prevent deletion IAM-user-initiated. How to enforce undelete capability?","options":["A. RDS automated backups only","B. AWS Backup with cross-account vault, RDS enable Enhanced Monitoring with delete protection, DynamoDB point-in-time recovery enabled, S3 Object Lock for database exports, CloudTrail logs deletion attempts, automated restore from backup on accidental deletion alert via EventBridge","C. Keep manual backup","D. Resource locking policy"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Backup provides recovery capability. RDS delete protection + PITR provides safety net. Object Lock ensures immutable backups. CloudTrail + EventBridge enables automated restore on deletion."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 250-account organization implements least-privilege resource naming: prod-eu-db-mysql-01, test-us-app-lambda-03. Teams must follow naming convention or resources tagged as non-compliant. How to enforce at creation time?","options":["A. Config rules detect non-compliant names after creation","B. CloudFormation parameter validation enforces naming regex, SCPs require tags matching name pattern, Lambda custom resource validates resource name at creation (deny if non-compliant), Webhook via EventBridge enforces for CLI/API creates","C. Teams request name approval","D. Manual audit quarterly"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFormation parameter validation prevents non-compliant names at template level. Lambda custom resource denies non-compliant CLI/API creates. Combined: 100% compliance without manual review."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your organization with 180 accounts implements automated resource expiration: ephemeral resources (test databases, dev compute) auto-delete after TTL (7 days). No manual cleanup needed. How to architect?","options":["A. CloudFormation stack deletion after TTL","B. ResourceGroups with lifecycle tag (CreatedAt timestamp), Lambda daily job queries by creation time, deletes resources > 7 days old, SNS alerts team before deletion, ConfigManagment documents for safe deletion (stop before delete)","C. Manual deletion reminders","D. Manual cleanup by team"],"answer":1,"explain":"ResourceGroups + Lambda enables automated expiration. SNS alerts prevent surprise deletion. Systems Manager documents ensure safe deletion (stop before remove). Reduces clutter automatically."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization needs a global content distribution network serving 1B requests/day with custom caching rules. Edge location redundancy critical. What architecture balances performance, cost, and complexity?","options":["A. Single CloudFront distribution with 200+ edges","B. CloudFront regional distributions per region (Americas, EU, Asia) with cross-region failover via Route 53, Origin Shield for cache acceleration (10-30% cost), Lambda@Edge for custom origin selection based on latency/region, real-time monitoring via CloudFront metrics","C. Global Accelerator only","D. Regional ALBs with Route 53"],"answer":1,"explain":"Regional CloudFront distributions optimize for geography. Origin Shield amortizes origin load. Lambda@Edge enables custom routing. Cross-region failover via Route 53. 1B requests/day feasible."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your organization runs machine learning inference at scale: 10M requests/second for real-time predictions. Model is 500MB. Latency SLA: P99 < 50ms. How to architecture endpoints across regions?","options":["A. Single SageMaker endpoint in primary region","B. Multi-region SageMaker endpoints with auto-scaling, regional traffic routing via Route 53 latency policy, model caching via ElastiCache Redis (inference results cached), batch inference via SageMaker Batch Transform for non-real-time, cost optimization via Spot Instances for batch","C. Lambda function for inference","D. Serverless inference via Lambda"],"answer":1,"explain":"Multi-region endpoints enable local inference <50ms. Route 53 latency routing directs traffic. ElastiCache Redis caches results. Batch Transform for non-latency workloads. Spot Instances reduce batch costs."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization runs 200+ legacy web applications (PHP, Java, .NET). Different deployment models (monolith, modular). Cloud migration requires minimal refactoring. How to modernize incrementally?","options":["A. Containerize all apps first","B. Elastic Beanstalk for language-specific runtimes (Java, PHP, .NET), CodePipeline for CI/CD, RDS for databases (Aurora for new, RDS for legacy), gradual refactoring to microservices via Lambda (high-ROI functions first), API Gateway facade for new features","C. Rewrite all applications","D. Keep on-premises indefinitely"],"answer":1,"explain":"Beanstalk preserves language runtime familiarity. Gradual refactoring via Lambda (new features only). API facade enables progressive modernization. Minimal large-scale refactoring risk."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your organization operates legacy billing system (COBOL, mainframe). Complex business logic, 40-year history of patches. Migration risk: high. How to mitigate?","options":["A. Rewrite entirely in Java","B. AWS Mainframe Modernization program: automated COBOL-to-Java conversion, parallel system for dual validation (legacy + new), run 6 months in parallel, gradual traffic shift (5% per week to new system), rollback plan (if issues, revert to legacy), API compatibility layer for downstream systems","C. Emulate mainframe in AWS","D. Keep mainframe on-prem indefinitely"],"answer":1,"explain":"Parallel validation reduces risk. Dual-run for 6 months proves equivalence. Gradual traffic shift. Rollback plan. Automated conversion. Minimizes business disruption."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization implements automated cost avoidance: prevent expensive operations before they occur. Expensive operations: cross-region data transfer ($0.02/GB), DynamoDB on-demand at peak ($25K/month spike), multi-AZ (2x cost). How to prevent?","options":["A. Alerts when costs high","B. SCPs deny cross-region transfer for non-critical workloads, DynamoDB provisioned capacity with predictive scaling (prevents on-demand spikes), single-AZ for dev/test (except prod which requires HA), cost forecasting via CUR ML model predicts spikes, team empowered to optimize before crossing threshold","C. Manual cost review","D. Accept cost overages"],"answer":1,"explain":"SCP prevents cross-region transfer. DynamoDB provisioned capacity + predictive scaling prevents spikes. Forecasting enables proactive optimization. Cost avoidance > cost reduction."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your organization is cost-aware SaaS: per-customer COGS goal $5. Current: $8. How to optimize to meet margin targets?","options":["A. Price increase (lose customers)","B. Right-sizing per customer tier (starter: shared RDS, professional: dedicated RDS, enterprise: aurora), auto-scaling per tier, compute optimization via Graviton instances (20% cheaper), storage optimization via Intelligent-Tiering, per-customer cost tracking enables customer-specific pricing","C. Accept lower margins","D. Eliminate unprofitable customers"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tiered deployment architecture. Graviton reduces compute cost 20%. Intelligent-Tiering reduces storage. Auto-scaling eliminates idle. Per-customer tracking enables precision pricing."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 180-account org needs multi-account incident response. Incident in account A should isolate account, preserve logs, alert incident team, notify other accounts. How to automate?","options":["A. Manual incident response","B. EventBridge aggregator detects GuardDuty findings, Lambda applies quarantine SCP to source account, SNS alerts incident team across accounts, CloudTrail/Macie logs quarantine event, automated rollback after 24hrs if cleared","C. Per-account manual response","D. No automation"],"answer":1,"explain":"EventBridge + Lambda quarantine + SNS notifications. CloudTrail audit. 24hr rollback. Automated incident containment."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 200-account org with 10K+ resources needs compliance attestation monthly. Proof that X% resources meet standard Y. How to automate evidence collection?","options":["A. Manual Config review","B. Security Hub standards compliance dashboard per account (aggregator), Config conformance packs prove evidence, scheduled monthly export to S3 (PDF report), third-party auditor API integration for automated evidence submission","C. Spreadsheet attestation","D. Manual compliance review"],"answer":1,"explain":"Security Hub dashboard. Config packs provide evidence. Scheduled export. Third-party audit API. Monthly attestation automated."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 150-account org implements cross-account backup/restore testing. Production RDS database must be restored to test account weekly, validated, then deleted. How to automate safely?","options":["A. Manual weekly restore test","B. AWS Backup automated snapshots, Systems Manager automation weekly: cross-account restore to test account, Lambda data validation (row count, checksums), auto-delete test DB after validation, SNS alerts on failure, RTO/RPO verified weekly","C. Monthly restore testing","D. No restore testing"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Backup + Systems Manager automation. Lambda validation. Auto-cleanup. Weekly RTO/RPO verification automated."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 210-account org needs resource-level encryption key access audit: who accessed which encryption key when. AWS KMS CloudTrail logs this. How to alert on suspicious access patterns?","options":["A. CloudTrail only (no analysis)","B. CloudTrail Lake for real-time KMS API queries, EventBridge rule on suspicious patterns (access outside business hours, unusual principals), Lambda investigation (list decrypt operations per key), SNS alerts security team, quarterly key rotation audit","C. Manual KMS audit","D. No access tracking"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudTrail Lake enables real-time KMS API analysis. EventBridge suspicious pattern detection. Lambda investigation. Automated security alerts."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 190-account org enforces tagging compliance. Non-compliant resources (missing tags) automatically quarantined (no traffic). Teams must tag within 24hrs or resource deleted. How to implement safely?","options":["A. Immediate deletion on non-compliance","B. Config rule detects untagged resources, Lambda tags with default values (infers from resource type + account), SNS notifies team, 24hr grace period to correct tags, auto-delete after grace period if still non-compliant","C. No enforcement","D. Manual team tagging"],"answer":1,"explain":"Config detection + Lambda auto-tag + 24hr grace + SNS notification. Balances compliance enforcement with team flexibility."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 220-account org needs to prevent secrets in CloudFormation parameters. Developers must use Secrets Manager, not template parameters. How to enforce?","options":["A. Training and trust developers","B. SCPs deny CloudFormation parameter creation with 'secret' or 'password' keywords, Lambda validates template before execution (deny if hard-coded secrets), Secrets Manager required via SCP (deny PassRole unless role has Secrets Manager permissions)","C. No enforcement","D. Manual template review"],"answer":1,"explain":"SCP denies secret parameters. Lambda template validation. Secrets Manager mandate. Multi-layered enforcement prevents accidental leaks."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 200-account org with SCPs needs to audit: which SCPs actually deny what? SCP conflicts causing resource creation failures. How to analyze SCP impact?","options":["A. Manual SCP review","B. AWS Access Analyzer for unused permissions, Config rules test resource creation with different principals, EventBridge on CreateFailed events, Lambda analyzes SCP denial reason (DeniedByPolicy), quarterly SCP impact report","C. Enable all SCPs (risky)","D. No SCP auditing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Access Analyzer + Config rules test SCPs. EventBridge on failures. Lambda analyzes denial reasons. Quarterly impact reports prevent over-blocking."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 185-account org needs cross-region disaster recovery for critical systems. Failover must happen automatically within 5 minutes. Business has never tested failover. How to de-risk?","options":["A. No DR testing (risky)","B. Monthly automated DR drill: EventBridge trigger → Route 53 failover to secondary region, validate application health (ALB target checks), automatic failback after 1hr, SNS alerts team, RTO < 5min verified monthly","C. Annual manual DR test","D. No DR capability"],"answer":1,"explain":"Monthly automated DR drill. Route 53 failover. Health checks validate. Auto-failback. RTO < 5min proven repeatedly."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 240-account org with hybrid on-premises + AWS needs unified resource inventory. 100K+ resources across clouds. Inventory drift occurs (manual changes). How to detect drift automatically?","options":["A. Manual AWS Config + on-prem tools","B. AWS Systems Manager OpsCenter aggregates AWS inventory, on-prem inventory via custom agents, drift detection via Lambda (compare current vs desired), Config compliance rules validate drift, auto-remediation for drift (terraform reapply)","C. No inventory tracking","D. Separate inventories"],"answer":1,"explain":"Systems Manager OpsCenter + custom agents. Lambda drift detection. Config compliance. Auto-remediation via Terraform. Unified hybrid inventory."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 195-account org needs per-department cost transparency. Departments see only own costs, can't see other departments' costs. How to implement secure cost visibility?","options":["A. Cost Explorer per account (limited)","B. CUR to S3, Redshift with row-level security (RLS) per department (Cognito identity determines accessible rows), QuickSight with RLS (department can only see own rows), cost reports auto-generated per department via Lambda, scheduled delivery to department finance","C. Shared Cost Explorer (no isolation)","D. No cost visibility"],"answer":1,"explain":"Redshift + RLS per department. QuickSight RLS. Lambda auto-report. Secure per-department cost visibility without manual distribution."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org needs federated machine learning: train models on-premises data without moving data to cloud. Data residency strict. How to architect ML pipeline?","options":["A. Export data to cloud (non-compliant)","B. SageMaker Federated Learning via AWS IoT Greengrass, on-prem compute trains local models, gradient updates (not data) sent to cloud, SageMaker aggregates gradients, converged model sent back on-prem, repeat for next iteration, data never leaves on-prem","C. On-premises ML only","D. Manual federated learning"],"answer":1,"explain":"SageMaker Federated Learning via Greengrass. Gradients only (not data) exchanged. Data residency maintained. Model converges across on-prem + cloud."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org runs real-time bidding auctions (advertising): 100K bids/second, <50ms decision latency, bid amounts 0.1 to 100 cents (huge variance). How to optimize cost + latency?","options":["A. RDS for bid database","B. DynamoDB for bid state (<10ms), Lambda for auction logic (provisioned concurrency), ElastiCache Redis for recent bid cache (<1ms), SQS for async winner processing, Kinesis for bid stream analytics","C. EC2 cluster","D. Custom C++ binary"],"answer":1,"explain":"DynamoDB + Redis < 50ms latency. Lambda provisioned concurrency. SQS async winner. 100K bids/sec at <50ms P99."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org operates social network: 500M users, real-time notifications (friend online, message received), feed generation. How to scale notification system?","options":["A. Email notifications daily","B. Kinesis Data Streams for notification events, Lambda fan-out to user-specific SQS queues, DynamoDB for user notification state, API Gateway WebSocket for push notifications, ElastiCache Redis for feed cache","C. Polling API only","D. No real-time notifications"],"answer":1,"explain":"Kinesis + Lambda fan-out. WebSocket for push. DynamoDB state. Redis feed cache. 500M users, real-time notifications."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org needs anomaly detection across 1M IoT sensors. Billions of data points daily. Detect anomalies in <1 second. How to architect?","options":["A. CloudWatch metrics only (sampled)","B. Kinesis Data Analytics for real-time anomaly detection (statistical models), S3 for archive, Lambda for alerting, threshold-based + ML-based detection (isolation forest), SageMaker re-trains models weekly","C. Batch analysis nightly","D. Manual threshold alerts"],"answer":1,"explain":"Kinesis Analytics real-time anomaly detection. Isolation forest ML model. SageMaker retraining. 1B data points/day at <1s latency."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org runs multiplayer game with dynamic in-game economy: player trading, item pricing, market clearing. Prices must be consistent across regions in near real-time. How to implement?","options":["A. Region-specific markets (inconsistent)","B. Global DynamoDB table (strong consistency per region, eventual cross-region), pricing Lambda triggered by trades, market maker Lambda for price adjustment, EventBridge for trade broadcasts, cross-region consistency <2sec","C. Centralized pricing server (latency)","D. Manual pricing"],"answer":1,"explain":"DynamoDB Global Table for pricing. Lambda market maker. EventBridge broadcasts. <2s cross-region consistency. Multiplayer economy at scale."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org manages IoT fleet: 1M devices, firmware must update with zero downtime, rollback capability if new firmware breaks devices. How to architect OTA updates?","options":["A. Manual update process","B. IoT Jobs for OTA (staged rollout: 10% → 50% → 100%), device heartbeat monitoring (if device stops reporting, rollback job), firmware signed (prevent unauthorized updates), metrics via CloudWatch (update success rate), rollback triggered by health check failure","C. Push updates to all devices (risky)","D. Manual update per device"],"answer":1,"explain":"IoT Jobs staged rollout + heartbeat monitoring. Signed firmware. CloudWatch metrics. Auto-rollback on health check failure. 1M device OTA safe."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org builds e-commerce platform: 10M products, inventory real-time, customer orders immediately processed. Order processing must be ACID (all-or-nothing). How to handle inventory + payment atomicity?","options":["A. Payment first, then inventory (risky)","B. DynamoDB transactions (ACID, up to 25 items per transaction), order transaction: check inventory, reserve quantity, charge payment, all-or-nothing. Failure → rollback all, SQS for async fulfillment","C. Eventual consistency (risky)","D. Manual order processing"],"answer":1,"explain":"DynamoDB transactions guarantee ACID. Order = inventory + payment atomic. SQS async fulfillment. 10M products, real-time inventory."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org needs fraud detection at checkout: 1M checkouts/hour, decision <100ms, false positive <0.5% (legitimate customers blocked). How to architect scoring?","options":["A. Simple rule-based scoring (high false positive)","B. Feature engineering: user history (DynamoDB), device fingerprinting, geolocation, payment method history, Lambda ML model combines signals (SageMaker), decision <100ms (provisioned concurrency), feedback loop updates model weekly via SageMaker","C. Async fraud detection (too slow)","D. No fraud detection"],"answer":1,"explain":"DynamoDB user history. Feature engineering pipeline. SageMaker ML model. Lambda provisioned concurrency. 1M/hr at <100ms with <0.5% false positive."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org operates container orchestration: 10K containers across ECS + Kubernetes clusters. Need unified logging, monitoring, deployment. How to manage heterogeneous infrastructure?","options":["A. Separate tools per platform","B. CloudWatch Logs for centralized logging (ECS + EKS via Fluent Bit), X-Ray for distributed tracing, CloudFormation for ECS + Terraform for EKS (infrastructure as code), EventBridge for event-driven deployments across platforms","C. Manual management","D. EKS only"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudWatch Logs + X-Ray unified observability. CloudFormation + Terraform IaC. EventBridge orchestrates both platforms. 10K containers managed."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org needs to compress video on-demand: customers upload video, system generates thumbnails + poster frame, different resolutions (480p, 720p, 1080p, 4K). Process 10K videos/day. Cost-sensitive. How to scale?","options":["A. MediaConvert for all videos (expensive)","B. S3 upload → Lambda fanout, smart routing: small files (Lambda Layers for ffmpeg), large files (MediaConvert), thumbnails via native Lambda, cost: $0.10 per video vs $1.00 MediaConvert","C. Manual ffmpeg on EC2","D. Third-party service"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hybrid approach: Lambda for small files, MediaConvert for large. Cost optimization. 10K videos/day at $0.10/video efficient."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org runs data lake with open data access: 500 internal teams + 100 external partners. Data governance: sensitive data only accessible internally. How to enforce access controls?","options":["A. Separate buckets per team","B. Lake Formation with data classification (sensitive, internal, public), cross-account role-based access (external = partner account, internal = employee account), table-level and column-level permissions, audit via CloudTrail","C. No access control (risky)","D. Manual permission management"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lake Formation classification + role-based access. Column-level permissions. Cross-account roles for partners. Audit via CloudTrail. Data sharing at scale."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org needs global name resolution: internal DNS for 100K corporate resources (servers, databases, services). On-premises + AWS (hybrid). How to provide unified DNS?","options":["A. Separate DNS per environment","B. Route 53 private hosted zone, on-premises DNS resolver (Route 53 Resolver endpoint) for hybrid, conditional forwarding rules, VPC endpoints for service discovery, CloudWatch for resolver query logs","C. Keep separate DNS","D. No service discovery"],"answer":1,"explain":"Route 53 private zones + Resolver endpoints. Conditional forwarding for hybrid. CloudWatch query logs. Unified DNS across 100K resources."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org manages APIs for partners: 50+ partners, each needs different rate limits, different API versions, different features. How to manage without creating 50 API Gateways?","options":["A. Single API Gateway, manage via auth context","B. Single API Gateway with usage plans per partner (rate limit per API key), API Versioning via header/path (v1, v2), stage variables per partner (feature flags), auto-generated API docs per partner","C. Separate API per partner","D. No partner APIs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Single API Gateway + usage plans. API versioning. Stage variables for feature flags. Scales to 50+ partners without multiplication."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org runs recommendation engine: 10M users, 100K items. Cold-start problem (new users, new items). How to handle cold-start recommendations?","options":["A. Popularity-based recommendations for all (no personalization)","B. Hybrid model: collaborative filtering (warm users/items), content-based (new items), popularity (new users), SageMaker retraining daily on new data, A/B testing different models (control vs treatment), user feedback loop for model improvement","C. No recommendations for new users","D. Random recommendations"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hybrid cold-start strategy. Collaborative + content-based + popularity. SageMaker daily retraining. A/B testing. User feedback loop. Cold-start solved."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org needs time-series forecasting: stock prices, demand prediction, weather patterns. 1B data points. Retrain models weekly. How to scale?","options":["A. Single SageMaker notebook (slow)","B. S3 data lake (Parquet), SageMaker Data Wrangler for preprocessing (parallel execution), built-in Forecast algorithm (DeepAR for 1B points), auto-retrain weekly via EventBridge, API for real-time inference via Lambda","C. Local Jupyter notebook","D. Manual forecasting"],"answer":1,"explain":"SageMaker Forecast handles 1B points. Data Wrangler parallel preprocessing. Weekly auto-retrain. Lambda inference API. Time-series at scale."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org has on-prem CI/CD pipeline (Jenkins, custom orchestration). Cloud migration: preserve pipeline, minimize changes. How to migrate?","options":["A. Rewrite pipeline for CodePipeline","B. AWS CodePipeline with CodeBuild, import Jenkins jobs via JCasc (Jenkins as Code), parallel to Jenkins for validation (dual-pipeline 2 weeks), gradual Jenkins → CodePipeline transition, artifact repository migration (S3 + CodeArtifact)","C. Keep Jenkins on-prem","D. Manual deployments"],"answer":1,"explain":"CodePipeline + CodeBuild preserves CI/CD patterns. JCasc imports Jenkins config. Dual validation. Gradual transition. No pipeline interruption."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org runs on-prem service mesh (Istio, custom networking). Cloud migration to AWS: AWS App Mesh provides mesh-like features. How to minimize refactoring?","options":["A. Rewrite services for App Mesh","B. AWS App Mesh with sidecar injection (Envoy proxies), traffic policies (retry, timeout, circuit breaker), gradual migration per service, parallel testing (old + new mesh), canary deployments via traffic split","C. No mesh in cloud","D. Keep Istio on-prem"],"answer":1,"explain":"App Mesh sidecar injection minimal code change. Traffic policies via config. Canary deployments with traffic split. Gradual service-by-service migration."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org has on-prem identity federation (ADFS). Cloud migration: use AWS SSO. How to maintain identity federation without breaking access?","options":["A. Switch all to AWS SSO immediately (risky)","B. AWS SSO with SAML federation to existing ADFS, parallel ADFS + SSO (gradual user migration 5% per week), application redirection to SSO post-migration, password resets via self-service portal","C. Keep ADFS on-prem","D. Local IAM users in AWS"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS SSO + SAML federation to ADFS. Parallel operation. Gradual user migration. Self-service portal. No access disruption."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org has on-prem secrets management (HashiCorp Vault). Cloud migration: AWS Secrets Manager provides vault-like capability. How to migrate secrets?","options":["A. Manual export/import","B. AWS Secrets Manager import, Vault agent on EC2 (on-prem) routes to AWS Secrets Manager via VPC endpoint, dual-read pattern (Vault + Secrets Manager), gradual application migration to Secrets Manager client","C. Keep Vault on-prem","D. IAM roles instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"Secrets Manager import. Vault agent bridge. Dual-read validation. Gradual application migration. No secret re-generation needed."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org runs NoSQL database (HBase on Hadoop). Cloud migration options: DynamoDB (managed) or HBase on EMR (self-managed). How to choose?","options":["A. DynamoDB only","B. TCO: DynamoDB requires schema refactoring (query patterns), EMR HBase minimal refactoring but ops overhead. Choose DynamoDB if refactoring time < 3 months ROI (on-going ops savings). Gradual migration possible via dual-write pattern.","C. Keep HBase on-prem","D. Cassandra instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"TCO analysis: DynamoDB cheaper but requires refactoring. EMR preserves HBase compatibility. Dual-write enables gradual migration."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org has network appliances (Palo Alto, F5 firewalls). Cloud migration: AWS WAF, Network Firewall replace appliances. How to migrate without downtime?","options":["A. Cutover all appliances immediately","B. AWS WAF + Network Firewall rules imported from appliances, parallel firewall (cloud + on-prem during transition), health checks on both, gradual traffic shift via Route 53 (5% per day to AWS firewall), retire appliances after validation","C. Keep appliances indefinitely","D. No WAF/firewall in cloud"],"answer":1,"explain":"Parallel firewall transition. Rule import from appliances. Health checks both. Gradual traffic shift. Zero downtime migration."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org has on-prem message queue (ActiveMQ, RabbitMQ). Cloud migration: Amazon MQ vs SNS/SQS (different API). Which to choose for minimal refactoring?","options":["A. SNS/SQS (requires refactoring)","B. Amazon MQ for compatibility (ActiveMQ-compatible or RabbitMQ-compatible), dual-queue pattern (old + MQ during transition), application client library updates only (no code change), gradual message routing shift from on-prem to MQ","C. Keep on-prem queue","D. Manual message passing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon MQ preserves protocol compatibility. Dual-queue transition. Client library updates only. Gradual routing shift. Minimal refactoring."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org operates on-prem log aggregation (Splunk, ELK). Cloud migration: CloudWatch Logs vs OpenSearch vs Splunk Cloud. Which minimizes refactoring?","options":["A. Splunk Cloud (SaaS, no refactoring needed)","B. CloudWatch Logs (agent-based, minimal config change), but if ELK dependency high, Amazon OpenSearch (ELK-compatible). Cost: CloudWatch cheaper for AWS services, OpenSearch better for multi-source logs, Splunk Cloud best for feature parity.","C. Keep on-prem ELK","D. No log aggregation"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudWatch Logs minimal refactoring. OpenSearch ELK-compatible. Splunk Cloud feature parity. Cost/refactoring tradeoff."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org has on-prem container registry (Docker Registry, Harbor). Cloud migration: ECR provides registry-compatible interface. How to migrate images?","options":["A. Manual image re-build","B. ECR image replication from on-prem registry (manual push or AWS DataSync for large registry), lifecycle policies manage retention, cross-account ECR access via cross-account role, IAM-based access control replaces on-prem auth","C. Keep on-prem registry","D. Public Docker Hub"],"answer":1,"explain":"ECR replication from on-prem. Lifecycle policies. Cross-account roles. IAM access control. Registry migration with zero rebuilds."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org runs WebLogic on-prem (10K users, 50 GB app server instances). Cloud migration: AWS app server (Tomcat, JBoss) vs keeping WebLogic. How to choose?","options":["A. Rewrite for open-source app server (risky)","B. WebLogic on EC2 (preserves existing setup, licensing portable), or WebLogic Kubernetes service (managed WebLogic), or Elastic Beanstalk for Java workloads. Choose based on: if Kubernetes familiar, use Kubernetes service; if not, use Beanstalk.","C. Keep WebLogic on-prem","D. Migrate to Spring Boot"],"answer":1,"explain":"WebLogic on EC2 preserves setup. Kubernetes service managed option. Beanstalk simplest. Choice based on ops expertise."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org has Oracle Forms on-prem. Cloud migration: Oracle Forms Cloud or refactor to modern web UI. How to minimize refactoring?","options":["A. Refactor entire application (expensive, risky)","B. Oracle Forms on OCI with AWS-OCI interconnect, or Apex (Oracle's low-code platform) replacement for Forms, or keep Oracle Forms on-prem and migrate backend to AWS, Application Migration Service (MGN) for non-database workloads","C. Keep on-prem indefinitely","D. Completely rewrite in React"],"answer":1,"explain":"Oracle Forms on OCI (minimal refactoring). Apex replacement (low-code). Oracle Forms on-prem + AWS backend (hybrid). Depends on refactoring budget."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org runs SAP ERP + custom extensions. Cloud migration: SAP on AWS available via AWS Marketplace. How to ensure minimal disruption?","options":["A. Quick SAP on EC2 migration","B. SAP on AWS via AWS Marketplace (appliance image), database migration via AWS DMS, custom extension validation in parallel environment, cutover during maintenance window (4-8hr), rollback procedure pre-tested","C. Manual SAP migration","D. Re-implement on cloud-native platform"],"answer":1,"explain":"SAP Marketplace appliance. DMS for database. Parallel validation. Maintenance window cutover. Pre-tested rollback. Minimal disruption."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org has niche on-prem database (Progress OpenEdge, Informix). Cloud migration: limited AWS support. How to handle?","options":["A. Cloud-only databases (DynamoDB, Aurora)","B. AWS Database Migration Service supports some niche DBs (check compatibility), or EC2 self-managed instance (OpenEdge/Informix on Linux VM), or partner migration tools (Progress Cloud migration), or dual-run (on-prem + AWS) during transition","C. Keep on-prem forever","D. Replatform entire database"],"answer":1,"explain":"Check DMS support. EC2 self-managed if DMS unavailable. Partner tools available. Dual-run for validation."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org scales rapidly: cost grows 100% annually, but revenue grows 150%. How to manage cost growth while protecting margins?","options":["A. Freeze hiring (limit growth)","B. Unit economics tracking: cost per user/transaction, revenue per user/transaction, margin per customer. At 150% growth, cost can grow up to 150% and maintain margin (if revenue/cost ratio constant). Quarterly efficiency review ensures margins don't erode. Re-architecture per 50% scale milestone.","C. Raise prices (reduce growth)","D. Accept margin compression"],"answer":1,"explain":"Unit economics tracking. Cost per user drives optimization. Quarterly review. Milestone-based re-architecture. Margin maintained during 150% revenue growth."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org has multi-tenant SaaS: high-touch enterprise customers (custom features, dedicated infrastructure), standard customers (shared). How to allocate costs fairly?","options":["A. Equal cost per customer (unfair)","B. Tiered cost allocation: standard customers (shared infrastructure, cost per seat), enterprise customers (dedicated resources + markup). Per-customer cost tracking via tags, margin calculation drives pricing, high-cost customers charged accordingly, low-cost customers subsidize standard tier","C. All cost per customer equal","D. Enterprise customers cost-only (no margin)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tiered allocation model. Cost tracking per customer. Margin-based pricing. Enterprise markup. Cross-subsidization for standard tier."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org implements FinOps program. Current waste: unused Reserved Instances, idle compute, over-provisioned databases. Estimated waste: 20% of $10M = $2M. How to prioritize optimization?","options":["A. Fix all simultaneously (complex)","B. Optimization roadmap: Month 1 (RI optimization, marketplace sales, = $800K), Month 2 (compute right-sizing, spot instances, = $600K), Month 3 (database consolidation, = $400K), month 4 (storage tiering, = $200K), total: $2M savings over 4 months, resource allocation per month per team","C. No priority (do nothing)","D. Random optimization"],"answer":1,"explain":"Phased optimization roadmap. RI first (easy). Compute next. DB consolidation. Storage tiering. $2M saved over 4 months."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org runs long-running batch jobs: overnight ETL, daily ML training, weekly reporting. Spot instances save 80% but interruption risk. How to balance cost vs reliability?","options":["A. All on-demand (safe, expensive)","B. Tiered strategy: critical jobs (daily ML training) use on-demand (80% reliability), standard jobs (ETL) use Spot (20% failure rate acceptable with retry), cost: 50% savings overall. Checkpoint/resume for fault tolerance.","C. All Spot (risky)","D. All on-demand (expensive)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tiered Spot strategy. Critical jobs on-demand. Standard jobs Spot. Checkpoint/resume. 50% cost savings with high reliability."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org moves from CapEx (hardware procurement) to OpEx (cloud). CFO concerned: CapEx predictable (multi-year), cloud OpEx variable. How to provide budget predictability?","options":["A. AWS commitment plans (Savings Plans, Reserved Instances) for baseline, on-demand for variable, forecasting model predicts total spend, committed + variable budget allocation","B. 100% Savings Plans (inflexible)","C. No budget planning (risky)","D. Keep CapEx hardware"],"answer":1,"explain":"Commitment plans for baseline. Forecasting for variable. Budget allocation baseline + buffer. Provides predictability while allowing growth."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org has NoSQL database (DynamoDB) with unpredictable traffic spikes (viral content, events). Peak: 10x average. On-demand mode auto-scales (cost-optimized). How to ensure cost doesn't explode during spikes?","options":["A. Provisioned capacity (cheaper, but under-spikes blocked)","B. On-demand with cost limits: DynamoDB auto-scales, cost anomaly detection alerts if exceeding 2x baseline, Lambda auto-remediation (cache aggressively, rate-limit users, queue excess traffic), max monthly cost cap via budget alert","C. Accept unlimited cost during spikes","D. Reject spikes (disable feature)"],"answer":1,"explain":"On-demand with guardrails. Cost anomaly detection. Lambda auto-remediation (cache, rate-limit). Cost cap. Handles spikes without bill shock."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org implements serverless-first strategy: Lambda, DynamoDB, S3. Cost model: per-execution + per-storage + per-data-transfer. How to optimize per-execution cost?","options":["A. Minimize Lambda memory (slower, longer duration)","B. Right-size Lambda memory based on CPU need (faster execution = lower duration cost), batch operations (reduce invocation count), caching (ElastiCache Redis, CloudFront), CDN for data transfer (reduce egress cost)","C. Fixed memory size (waste)","D. Large memory always (expensive)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Right-sized Lambda memory. Batch operations. Caching. CDN. Optimizes duration + transfer cost per execution."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org uses Redshift for analytics: 40 nodes, $50K/month, utilization 40% (other times idle). How to reduce cost while maintaining query latency?","options":["A. Right-size to 16 nodes (risk of exceeding query time SLA)","B. Redshift Spectrum (query S3 directly instead of cluster), materialized views (cache hot queries), scheduled cluster start/stop (scale down off-hours), cost: 20 nodes on-demand + spectrum for cold data = $25K/month (50% savings), latency maintained via materialized views","C. Keep 40 nodes always","D. Migrate to Athena (different tool)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Spectrum for cold data queries. Materialized views for hot queries. Scheduled scaling. 50% cost reduction, latency maintained."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org has cross-region data replication: high-bandwidth replication costs $200K/year. Data includes both hot (accessed daily) and cold (accessed monthly). How to optimize replication cost?","options":["A. No replication (risk)","B. Selective replication: hot data replicated daily (cross-region), cold data replicated monthly (batch transfer via Snowball), on-demand restoration for rare cold data access, S3 transfer acceleration for cross-region, cost: $80K/year (60% savings)","C. Replicate all daily","D. Keep all in single region (risky)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Selective replication frequency. Hot data daily. Cold data monthly. Snowball batch. On-demand restoration. $80K/year 60% savings."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org implements FinOps org structure: cloud finance team (2 engineers), but 500+ developers provision resources. How to scale FinOps without adding staff?","options":["A. One FinOps engineer reviews all requests (bottleneck)","B. Self-service FinOps: cost allocation tags enforced by SCPs, cost dashboard self-service (team sees own costs), cost anomaly alerts to teams (not FinOps), automated remediation (Lambda fixes low-hanging fruit), FinOps team focuses on strategic optimization (cost models, pricing models)","C. No FinOps program","D. Hire 50 FinOps engineers"],"answer":1,"explain":"Self-service cost visibility. Automated remediation. FinOps team focuses on strategy. Scales to 500+ developers with 2 people."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 210-account org implements automated account factory. New business unit requests account via ServiceNow, auto-creates AWS account + applies guardrails + provisions VPC + enables logging within 30 minutes. How to architect?","options":["A. Manual account creation by AWS admin","B. ServiceNow integration via Lambda, Organizations CreateAccount API, Control Tower applies guardrails, CloudFormation StackSets provision VPC + logging, 30min SLA achieved via parallel provisioning","C. Manual account requests (weeks)","D. Pre-create accounts (wasteful)"],"answer":1,"explain":"ServiceNow → Lambda → Organizations API. Control Tower auto-applies. StackSets parallel. 30min SLA."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 190-account org implements automated security posture improvement. GuardDuty findings auto-remediated: excessive SSH access opens port 22, system closes it. But legitimate SSH access needed for maintenance. How to prevent breaking legitimate access?","options":["A. No auto-remediation (manual only)","B. GuardDuty finding triggers SQS (delay buffer), Lambda analyzes finding (is IP in approved list?), if approved, whitelist IP in security group before closing port 22, if unapproved, close port, SNS notifies team","C. Always close port 22","D. Never remediate findings"],"answer":1,"explain":"Delay buffer + IP whitelist check. Approved IPs exempted. Unapproved IPs blocked. SNS notification. Balances security + operations."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 220-account org needs identity recertification monthly: management confirms employees still need their roles. Current: 10K+ roles, manual review 40 hours/month. How to automate?","options":["A. No recertification (risky)","B. IAM Access Analyzer + Identity Center, monthly audit of active role sessions (CloudTrail), email managers with report (who accessed what), require confirmation via link, auto-revoke if no confirmation after 2 weeks","C. Quarterly manual review","D. Annual recertification only"],"answer":1,"explain":"IAM Access Analyzer + CloudTrail analysis. Email managers. Link-based confirmation. Auto-revoke on silence. 40hr/month reduced to 5hr/month."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 200-account org manages AWS account lifecycle: creation, active use, scheduled decommission. How to enforce that abandoned accounts are decommissioned?","options":["A. No enforcement (accounts stay forever)","B. IAM policy: on day 90 of no API activity (CloudTrail analysis), tag account as abandoned, day 100: SNS alert owner, day 110: auto-decommission (backup resources to S3, delete accounts), exception process for legitimate inactive (data archive)","C. Manual decommission","D. Keep all accounts indefinitely"],"answer":1,"explain":"Activity-based tagging. Progressive alerts. Auto-decommission after 110 days. Exception process. Accounts automatically lifecycle."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 175-account org implements network architecture review: all VPCs + VPC peering + routing tables audited quarterly for security. 500+ resources. How to automate review?","options":["A. Manual AWS Console audit","B. Config conformance packs for network rules, VPC Flow Logs for connectivity analysis, Lambda generates architecture diagram (GraphML format), security team reviews diagram + flowlogs, CloudTrail logs all network changes, quarterly report auto-generated","C. No audit (risky)","D. Manual spreadsheet"],"answer":1,"explain":"Config packs + VPC Flow Logs. Lambda generates diagrams. Auto-reporting. Quarterly review workflow. 500+ resources reviewed automatically."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 210-account org needs compliance certification: every 3 months, certify infrastructure meets standard X. Currently: manual attestation (error-prone, 100+ hours). How to automate?","options":["A. Spreadsheet-based attestation","B. AWS Audit Manager automates evidence collection (Config rules, CloudTrail logs, etc.), generates compliance report per standard, requires manager certification (electronic signature), tracks certifications per account/region, historical evidence retained 7 years","C. No formal compliance tracking","D. Manual spreadsheet quarterly"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Audit Manager automates evidence. Electronic signatures. Historical retention. Compliance reports auto-generated. 100+ hours reduced to 5 hours."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 185-account org with distributed teams needs to enforce resource location: product team in EU creates resource in us-east-1 (should be eu-west-1). How to prevent data residency violations?","options":["A. Training only (not enforced)","B. SCPs deny all services in non-approved region per OU + team, Config rules detect out-of-region resources (daily check), Lambda auto-remediation (delete or move resource with alert), CloudTrail logs all violations","C. No enforcement","D. Manual audit monthly"],"answer":1,"explain":"SCP region restrictions. Config detection. Lambda remediation. CloudTrail audit. Data residency technically enforced."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 200-account org implements cost accountability: teams must stay within budget. How to enforce budget without breaking innovation?","options":["A. Hard budget cap (blocks needed spending)","B. Tiered enforcement: 80% alert, 90% approval required (manager can approve up to 110%), 100% block non-critical services (dev/test). Teams see budget vs spend real-time via QuickSight, monthly review adjusts budgets based on business growth","C. No budget enforcement","D. Unlimited spending"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tiered alerts with approval gates. Real-time visibility. Monthly adjustments. Balances accountability + flexibility."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org runs multi-protocol API platform: 50K RPS, REST (60%), GraphQL (25%), gRPC (15%). Clients expect sub-100ms response. How to route protocols efficiently?","options":["A. Single API Gateway (REST only)","B. Network Load Balancer with TLS SNI-based routing, API Gateway for REST/GraphQL (JSON over HTTP/2), gRPC service on separate target group (HTTP/2 native), unified API Key authentication via Lambda@Edge","C. Three separate endpoints","D. GraphQL only with transpilers"],"answer":1,"explain":"NLB SNI routing. API Gateway for REST/GraphQL. gRPC native HTTP/2. Unified auth. 50K RPS multi-protocol."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org operates IoT platform for industrial sensors: 10M sensors, readings every 10 seconds, data includes location, temperature, pressure. Real-time alerts if temperature abnormal. How to process 100M events/second?","options":["A. Kinesis Data Streams with simple processing","B. Kinesis Data Analytics for anomaly detection (statistical models), Timestream for time-series storage (optimized for sensor data), IoT Core for device management, Lambda for custom alerts, QuickSight for real-time dashboards","C. S3 + batch processing","D. Manual monitoring"],"answer":1,"explain":"Kinesis Analytics anomaly detection. Timestream for time-series. IoT Core management. 100M events/sec processed."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org runs graph database use case: social network (users, friendships, recommendations). 500M users, 5B friendships. Sub-second query latency. How to implement?","options":["A. DynamoDB with denormalization","B. Amazon Neptune (managed graph database), indexes on frequently queried properties, caching via ElastiCache (warm queries), read replicas for read scaling, full-text search via OpenSearch for user search","C. SQL JOIN queries (slow)","D. Manual graph traversal"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Neptune scales to 5B edges. Caching for warm queries. Read replicas. OpenSearch for search. Sub-second latency."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org needs complex event processing: detect fraud patterns in transactions (e.g., same card used in 2 countries in <1 hour). 1M events/second. Sub-100ms decision latency. How to detect patterns?","options":["A. Rule engine (hard-coded)","B. Kinesis Data Analytics for pattern matching, Kinesis windows (tumbling + sliding), Lambda for complex fraud rules (CEP), DynamoDB for transaction state (lookup same card recent locations), SNS for fraud alerts, estimated <100ms decision latency","C. Batch processing nightly","D. No fraud detection"],"answer":1,"explain":"Kinesis Analytics pattern matching. Lambda CEP logic. DynamoDB state. 1M events/sec at <100ms."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org implements edge intelligence: 1000+ edge locations with local inference, cloud training, model updates. Edge devices have limited compute (CPU-only, 1GB RAM). How to run inference efficiently at edge?","options":["A. Send raw data to cloud for inference (high latency)","B. SageMaker Neo compiles models for edge hardware (optimize for CPU), IoT Greengrass Core runs inference locally <100ms, cloud trains models weekly (SageMaker), IoT Jobs push updates (staged rollout), s3 model versioning","C. Kubernetes on edge (too heavy)","D. No edge inference"],"answer":1,"explain":"SageMaker Neo CPU optimization. Greengrass local inference. Cloud training. IoT Jobs distribution. <100ms edge inference."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org operates on-prem Elasticsearch: 100 nodes, 5M documents, 10K queries/sec. Cloud migration: AWS OpenSearch provides Elasticsearch compatibility. How to migrate zero-downtime?","options":["A. Snapshot + restore (requires reindexing)","B. Opensearch Snapshot API for initial backup, continuous replication via Logstash (on-prem → AWS), dual-read pattern (query both old + new), traffic shift via client config (5% per day to AWS), retire on-prem cluster after validation","C. Keep on-prem Elasticsearch","D. Reindex all documents"],"answer":1,"explain":"Snapshot + Logstash continuous replication. Dual-read validation. Gradual traffic shift. Zero-downtime migration."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org has legacy monolithic Java application (2M lines of code, 200 engineers). Cloud migration: monolith on Beanstalk. Modernize to microservices incrementally via strangler fig. How to manage dependencies?","options":["A. Extract all microservices first (risky)","B. Strangler fig: API Gateway in front of monolith, new features as microservices, legacy dependencies handled by Facade API, synchronous calls stay monolith (replace later), async messaging for new features, gradual monolith retirement","C. Keep monolith forever","D. Rewrite completely"],"answer":1,"explain":"Strangler fig pattern. API Gateway facade. New features as microservices. Gradual retirement. Minimizes risk."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org runs on-prem Windows domain: 20K servers in 10 forests, multi-site replication. Cloud migration: AWS Directory Service (Managed AD). How to maintain domain consistency?","options":["A. Single AWS Directory Service (limited to 1 forest)","B. AWS Directory Service with multi-site setup (AWS + on-prem), AD Connector for federation (on-prem LDAP trusts AWS AD), gradual DC promotion in AWS (replicas), site-to-site VPN for replication traffic, automated trust establishment between forests","C. Keep on-prem AD","D. Per-region AWS Directory Service (fragmented)"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Directory Service multi-site. AD Connector federation. Gradual DC migration. VPN replication. Domain parity."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org operates on-prem SFTP servers for customer file transfers. Cloud migration: AWS Transfer Family (managed SFTP). How to migrate without customer disruption?","options":["A. Customers re-point to new SFTP endpoint (requires customer action)","B. AWS Transfer Family endpoint created, DNS CNAME points to new endpoint, dual-run (on-prem + AWS) for 2 weeks, customers gradually connect to new endpoint (monitoring old for staleness), on-prem server decommissioned after 2 weeks of zero traffic","C. Keep on-prem SFTP","D. Require customers to migrate immediately"],"answer":1,"explain":"Parallel Transfer Family + on-prem. DNS CNAME update. Dual-run validation. Gradual customer migration. Customer-less disruption possible."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org runs 500 Lambda functions: mix of frequently called (1M/month) and rarely called (1K/month). Cost: $50K/month. How to optimize to $30K (40% savings)?","options":["A. All provisioned concurrency (expensive)","B. Provisioned concurrency only for high-volume functions (80/500 functions), standard concurrency for others, memory right-sizing per function (CloudWatch profiling), Lambda Layers for code reuse (reduce function size), cost: $30K achievable via selective provisioning + right-sizing","C. Reduce memory (slower)","D. Migrate to EC2"],"answer":1,"explain":"Selective provisioned concurrency. Right-sizing. Lambda Layers. 40% savings via optimization."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org migrates from on-premises (capex hardware $10M/year) to AWS (opex $5M/year). Year 1 cost: hardware depreciation $2M + AWS $5M = $7M (net positive). But CFO budget set for $10M on-prem model. How to align budgets?","options":["A. Request budget increase (difficult)","B. Phased migration: keep 50% on-prem (year 1: $5M hardware + $2.5M AWS = $7.5M, within budget), year 2: 25% on-prem ($2.5M + $3.75M = $6.25M), year 3: 0% on-prem ($5M AWS only). Total 3-year TCO same, but reduces year-over-year shock.","C. Accelerate migration, exceed budget","D. Stay on-prem"],"answer":1,"explain":"Phased migration aligns with budget. Year 1 $7.5M. Year 2 $6.25M. Year 3 $5M. No budget overrun."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org implements cost optimization: every engineer paid bonus if team achieves cost target (e.g., $10/user/month). How to prevent engineers from cutting legitimate features to save costs?","options":["A. No bonus (no incentive)","B. Dual metrics: cost target + quality metrics (latency, availability, feature count). Bonus only if BOTH achieved. Cost incentive: up to 50% of savings. Quality guardrails: non-negotiable SLA + feature backlog tracking.","C. Cost only bonus (risky)","D. No cost optimization program"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dual metrics prevent quality erosion. Cost + quality both required. Shared savings incentive. Balanced optimization."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org uses Reserved Instances: purchased 10,000 × m5.large (3-year contract). Business changes mid-contract: only 5,000 needed. Loss: $2M if holding idle. How to minimize loss?","options":["A. Keep idle (lose $2M)","B. Sell 5,000 RIs on RI Marketplace at 70% value (recover $1.4M), loss only $600K. Alternatively: right-size to m6i (smaller, cheaper), purchase new RIs for m6i (offset loss via cost savings). Net loss: <$300K via strategy.","C. Terminate instances (still pay)","D. Unused indefinitely"],"answer":1,"explain":"RI Marketplace recover 70%. Right-size strategy. Dual approach minimizes loss to <$300K."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 160-account org implements automated backup testing for all databases. Failed restore test alerts team immediately. How to prevent test failures from blocking production?","options":["A. Run tests sequentially (slow)","B. AWS Backup cross-account restore (test account isolated), Lambda validation (fast-fail), parallel test execution per database, CloudWatch metrics track test pass rate, failed tests → SNS alert but production unaffected","C. Manual backup testing","D. No testing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cross-account isolation. Parallel execution. CloudWatch metrics. Production unaffected by test failures."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 170-account org implements automated security patch deployment: patch released, auto-apply to dev within 24hrs, test within 48hrs, prod within 72hrs. Patch failure → auto-rollback. How to implement safely?","options":["A. Manual patching per team","B. AWS Patch Manager with maintenance windows (dev 24hr, test 48hr, prod 72hr), Systems Manager automation applies patches, CloudWatch alarms on patch failure, auto-rollback to previous AMI version, SNS alerts team on failure","C. No patching schedule","D. Annual patches only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Patch Manager with tiered windows. Automation applies. Auto-rollback on failure. SNS alerts. Phased deployment reduces risk."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 200-account org needs to audit: which employees have AWS console access? Who accessed what? How to generate monthly report?","options":["A. Manual IAM user audit","B. AWS Access Analyzer for console access detection, CloudTrail logs all console sign-ins, Lambda generates monthly report (console users + last login date + actions per user), email report to security team, automate via EventBridge scheduled rule","C. No audit (risky)","D. Manual spreadsheet"],"answer":1,"explain":"Access Analyzer + CloudTrail. Lambda report generation. Automated scheduling. Monthly audit without manual effort."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 180-account org needs API rate limiting per customer (100 calls/hour for free, 10K/hour for premium). How to enforce without custom code?","options":["A. Application-level rate limiting (custom code)","B. API Gateway Usage Plans per customer tier, CloudWatch metrics track rate limit violations, Lambda throttle response (inform customer of limit), premium tier allows burst via SQS buffering","C. No rate limiting","D. All customers same limit"],"answer":1,"explain":"API Gateway Usage Plans per tier. CloudWatch metrics. Lambda throttle handling. SQS burst buffering. No custom code."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 195-account org implements cost governance: each team budget $50K/month. Overspend detected: auto-remediation or escalation? How to balance innovation + cost control?","options":["A. Hard block at budget (kills innovation)","B. Cost threshold tiers: 75% = warning, 90% = manager approval required (fast approval, 1 day), 110% = CFO escalation, exception process for legitimate overages, teams see real-time spend via dashboard","C. No limits (risky)","D. Soft limits only (no enforcement)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tiered thresholds with approval gates. Real-time visibility. Exception process. Balances control + flexibility."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 210-account org needs to retire resources: RDS instance marked for deletion (end-of-support), must delete all snapshots + automated backups before deletion. How to enforce order?","options":["A. Manual deletion in correct order (error-prone)","B. Config rule detects unmarked databases, Lambda generates deletion plan (snapshots first, then DB), execution via Systems Manager automation (step-by-step with approval gates), CloudTrail logs all deletions","C. Automatic immediate deletion (risky)","D. No deletion enforcement"],"answer":1,"explain":"Config detection + Lambda planning. Systems Manager orchestrates order. Approval gates. CloudTrail audit. Safe deletion workflow."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org runs recommendation engine: expensive ML model training (8hr per week). Inference happens 1M times/day. How to optimize cost without sacrificing quality?","options":["A. Daily model retraining (expensive)","B. Batch model training weekly (8hr), SageMaker inference endpoint (CPU-only cheaper), A/B testing old vs new model (canary 5% of traffic), ensemble predictions (weighted blend), cost: 70% reduction vs daily retraining","C. Single static model (stale recommendations)","D. No ML recommendations"],"answer":1,"explain":"Weekly batch training. CPU-only inference. A/B testing. Ensemble predictions. 70% cost reduction."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org operates analytics platform: dashboard queries (1 sec), ad-hoc queries (1 min), background ML jobs (1 hr). Mixed workload. How to optimize warehouse cost?","options":["A. Single Redshift cluster with all workloads","B. Redshift for dashboard (provisioned), Athena for ad-hoc (on-demand pay-per-query), EMR for ML jobs (Spot instances), cost: dashboard $10K, ad-hoc $2K, ML $1K vs $25K single cluster","C. Separate cluster per workload (overhead)","D. No optimization"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tiered architecture. Redshift dashboard. Athena ad-hoc. EMR ML. 85% cost reduction vs single cluster."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org needs to run complex simulations: weather prediction, financial modeling. 10K CPU cores needed for 6 hours daily. Fault-tolerant. Budget: minimize compute cost. How to implement?","options":["A. EC2 on-demand (expensive)","B. AWS Batch with Spot Instances (80% savings), checkpoints every 1hr (fault tolerance), auto-scaling to 10K cores as needed, S3 for simulation results, cost: $200/day vs $1000 on-demand","C. On-premises cluster (capex)","D. Lambda (limited compute)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Batch + Spot 80% savings. Checkpoints every 1hr. Auto-scaling. 10K cores for $200/day."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org operates blockchain-based supply chain: track shipments globally, immutable audit trail. 1M shipments/day, ledger grows 100GB/month. How to store ledger cost-effectively?","options":["A. Amazon QLDB (managed blockchain)","B. QLDB for transaction logging (immutable), S3 for ledger archival (Glacier after 90 days, Deep Archive after 1yr, cost ~$1K/month vs enterprise blockchain $100K+)","C. Custom blockchain implementation","D. No ledger"],"answer":1,"explain":"QLDB immutable ledger. S3 archive with tiering. 99% cheaper than enterprise blockchain."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org has legacy investment portfolio system (COBOL, 30 years old, mission-critical). Cloud migration risk: extremely high. How to minimize risk?","options":["A. Big-bang cutover (risky)","B. Strangler fig: new investment orders via cloud API, legacy handles existing portfolio (gradually depletes), parallel validation for 12 months, rollback capability maintained throughout, automated reconciliation daily","C. Keep on-prem indefinitely","D. Rewrite entirely"],"answer":1,"explain":"Strangler fig + parallel validation. 12-month dual-run. Daily reconciliation. Rollback ready. Zero downtime possible."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org runs custom CRM on-prem. Cloud migration: buy Salesforce (CRM as a Service) or build on AWS? TCO analysis needed.","options":["A. Salesforce immediately (expensive)","B. TCO 5-year: Salesforce $1M/year + customization $200K = $6M total, AWS-based CRM $200K migration + $100K/year + 2 engineers ($200K/year) = $2.2M total. Choose AWS-based if in-house engineering < Salesforce cost. Hybrid: Salesforce + custom extensions via AWS Lambda.","C. Keep legacy CRM","D. Build custom from scratch"],"answer":1,"explain":"TCO comparison shows AWS-based cheaper if engineering available. Hybrid option (Salesforce + Lambda extensions) balances cost/effort."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org runs 24/7 workload with predictable hourly variation (peak 8am-6pm, off-peak other). Cost: $50K/month all on-demand. How to reduce via scheduling?","options":["A. Reserve 50% baseline (24/7)","B. Baseline: Reserved Instances (24/7), peak hours: on-demand (8am-6pm only), auto-scaling to handle peak, cost: $20K baseline (RI) + $15K peak (on-demand) = $35K/month (30% savings)","C. Keep all on-demand","D. Off-peak shutdown (breaks services)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Reserve baseline (24/7). On-demand peak (8am-6pm). Auto-scaling peak hours. 30% savings."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org operates SaaS: unit economics $5/customer/month cost, price $15/customer/month. As scale increases 10x, cost per unit increases (data transfer, compute increases). How to prevent margin erosion?","options":["A. Accept lower margins (risky)","B. Cost optimization roadmap: caching (reduce compute 20%), CDN (reduce transfer 30%), database optimization (reduce storage 15%), total: cost/unit reduces to $3 (40% improvement), maintain $15 price → margin expands","C. Increase price","D. No optimization"],"answer":1,"explain":"Roadmap: caching + CDN + DB optimization. Cost/unit $5 → $3. Margin $10 → $12. Profitability improves at scale."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org uses Reserved Instances (400x m5.large 1-year). 6 months in, instance family prices drop (m6i 10% cheaper). How to avoid locking in old family?","options":["A. Keep old RIs (pay premium)","B. Flexible commitment: convert m5.large to m5.xlarge (same cost, right-size), or sell 200 RIs on RI Marketplace ($1.40/unit, recover 70%), buy m6i RIs with proceeds, net: locked-in pricing with flexibility via marketplace","C. Cancel RIs (pay penalty)","D. All on-demand (expensive)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Right-size to new family. RI Marketplace recovery. Flexibility via marketplace. Reduce premiums."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org has cloud bill: $5M/month. 20% is waste (idle resources, over-provisioning). How to identify + eliminate waste systematically?","options":["A. Random optimization attempts","B. Systematic waste identification: Compute Optimizer (right-sizing), AWS Trusted Advisor (unused resources), Cost Anomaly Detection (unusual spikes), Config rules (non-compliant resources), estimated: $1M waste identified/month, quarterly cleanup cycles","C. No waste identification","D. Accept waste"],"answer":1,"explain":"Systematic identification via multiple tools. Quarterly cleanup cycles. $1M/month waste elimination. Addresses root causes."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org implements chargeback to business units. IT costs $10M/year, distributed: compute $4M, storage $2M, network $2M, shared services $2M. How to allocate shared services fairly?","options":["A. Equal split per unit ($200K each, 50 units)","B. Shared services allocated per usage: compute team uses TGW (network charge), storage team uses encryption (security charge), Lambda team uses Secrets Manager (security charge), allocation: usage-driven, incentivizes optimization, enables precise cost attribution per business unit","C. No shared service allocation (buried in overhead)","D. Compute team pays all (unfair)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Usage-driven allocation. Incentivizes optimization. Precise cost attribution. Fair across teams."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org operates on-prem PostgreSQL: 5TB, 500 concurrent users. Cloud migration to RDS/Aurora needed. Binary compatibility 99% (99.99% SQL compatibility). How to migrate with minimal risk?","options":["A. AWS DMS for replication (standard path)","B. AWS DMS with binary replication (Logical Replication) for compatibility assurance, parallel Aurora cluster for validation (2 weeks), cross-validation queries on both systems, gradual application cutover (5% per day), rollback procedure pre-tested","C. Manual export/import","D. Keep on-prem PostgreSQL"],"answer":1,"explain":"DMS logical replication. Parallel validation. Gradual application cutover. Binary compatibility assured."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org has NetSuite ERP (cloud-based). On-prem extensions (custom code) interact with NetSuite via API. Cloud migration: keep extensions in cloud. How to minimize re-work?","options":["A. Rewrite extensions for cloud-native","B. Keep existing extensions on AWS (EC2 or Lambda), update API calls for cloud networking (VPC endpoints), deployment via CodePipeline, no business logic rewrite needed, cost: similar or lower vs on-prem hosting","C. Keep extensions on-prem","D. Eliminate extensions"],"answer":1,"explain":"Keep extensions logic. Update networking only. CodePipeline deployment. No business logic rewrite."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org needs multi-region active-active: databases sync across 3 regions, RPO < 1 second, RTO < 5 minutes. How to architect at scale?","options":["A. DynamoDB + Aurora in single region","B. DynamoDB Global Tables (RPO < 1s guaranteed), Aurora Global Database for SQL data, Route 53 health checks trigger region failover (automatic RTO <5min), data consistency eventual (strong within region)","C. Manual failover across regions","D. Single region only"],"answer":1,"explain":"DynamoDB Global Tables RPO <1s. Aurora Global DB. Route 53 automatic failover. Multi-region active-active."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org runs complex financial system: trades, settlement, accounting. Data: 100TB, queries: analytical (1hr+), real-time (sub-second). How to minimize database cost for mixed workload?","options":["A. Single database for all (performance trade-off)","B. Redshift for analytics (1hr+ queries), in-memory cache (DAX or Redis) for real-time (sub-second), S3 for archival (3+ years), cost: $15K Redshift + $5K cache vs $50K unified expensive database","C. Two separate databases (overhead)","D. On-premises database"],"answer":1,"explain":"Redshift analytics. In-memory cache real-time. S3 archive. 70% cost reduction vs single expensive database."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 200-account org needs to implement guardrails preventing any account from exceeding $10K/month cost. Overspend = account auto-quarantined. How to balance speed vs safety?","options":["A. Immediate quarantine (risky)","B. Cost threshold: $9K = alert, $10K = SCP blocks new creation (existing workloads continue), $11K = account audit by FinOps team, $12K = escalation to CFO, quarantine only if policy violated (not just cost)","C. No controls","D. Hard quarantine at $10K"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tiered controls based on cost levels. Alert → block creation → audit → escalation. Policy-based not just cost-based."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"A 240-account org needs to prevent shadow IT: unapproved SaaS tools, unapproved cloud services. How to enforce allowlist technically?","options":["A. Trust users (no enforcement)","B. SCPs deny CreateResource for non-approved services per OU, API Gateway allowlist for APIs, proxy all internet traffic through WAF (block unknown SaaS domains), Config rules detect non-compliant resources, exception process for approval","C. No enforcement","D. Manual approval per service"],"answer":1,"explain":"SCP service allowlist. API Gateway allowlist. WAF domain filter. Config rules detection. Multi-layered technical enforcement."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org needs distributed lock management for critical sections: 100K concurrent requests, mutual exclusion required, lock timeout 5 seconds. How to implement?","options":["A. DynamoDB conditional writes","B. Amazon ElastiCache (Redis Cluster) for lock manager (sub-millisecond latency), Redlock algorithm (mutual exclusion across nodes), lock TTL (5 seconds auto-expiry), Lambda for critical section code, estimated: <10ms lock acquisition","C. Database locking (slow)","D. Application-level locks"],"answer":1,"explain":"Redis Cluster + Redlock. TTL auto-expiry. <10ms lock acquisition. 100K concurrent safely."},{"cat":"migration-modernization","q":"Your org has EXA database on-premises. Cloud migration: AWS does not have EXA equivalent. How to approach?","options":["A. Keep on-prem indefinitely","B. AWS Alternative: RDS for MySQL/PostgreSQL (if replatformable), or Redshift (if analytical), or DynamoDB (if NoSQL acceptable). Migrate via AWS Database Migration Service + custom script for EXA-specific features. Evaluate replacement based on workload type.","C. Buy AWS-native licensed EXA","D. Manually convert schema"],"answer":1,"explain":"Identify EXA workload type. Map to AWS service (RDS, Redshift, DynamoDB). DMS + custom script migration. Phased evaluation."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org runs multi-tenant SaaS with 1000 customers. Per-customer cost varies 10x (large customers use more resources). How to build multi-tier pricing model that customers accept?","options":["A. Flat pricing (unfair to small customers)","B. Usage-based pricing: track per-customer: compute (vCPU-hours), storage (GB), data transfer (GB), build cost formula per metric, pricing = cost × 3x markup (enterprise, standard, startup tiers), transparent cost calculator for customers (build trust)","C. Fixed pricing per tier (inflexible)","D. Cost-plus dynamic pricing (opaque)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Usage-based pricing transparent. Per-customer cost tracking. Tiered markup. Cost calculator builds trust."},{"cat":"complex-org-design","q":"Your 180-account org needs to enforce security standards automatically. Non-compliant resources auto-tagged for remediation. How to prevent false positives?","options":["A. No verification (auto-remediate all)","B. Compliance detection: Config rule + manual verification (2-person rule), SNS alert before remediation (team can cancel), dry-run remediation (show what would change), approval gate for breaking changes (terminate resource requires CFO approval)","C. No auto-remediation (manual only)","D. Auto-remediate immediately (risky)"],"answer":1,"explain":"2-person rule for detection. SNS alerts before action. Dry-run preview. Approval gate for destructive actions."},{"cat":"new-solutions","q":"Your org implements disaster recovery for entire data center (100+ applications, heterogeneous infrastructure, RTO 4 hours). How to test DR without breaking production?","options":["A. Annual manual DR test (risky)","B. AWS Application Discovery Service maps dependencies, Replication Manager fails over to secondary region monthly (automated), CloudFormation validates environment (smoke tests), production traffic unaffected (secondary environment isolated), metrics validate RTO <4 hours","C. No DR testing","D. Manual DR procedure"],"answer":1,"explain":"Discovery Service + Replication Manager. Monthly automated failover test. Secondary environment isolated. RTO validated monthly."},{"cat":"cost-complexity","q":"Your org negotiates AWS pricing: $100M annual spend, request 25% discount. AWS offers 15%. How to bridge gap?","options":["A. Accept 15% (leave $10M on table)","B. Negotiation strategy: commit 3-year (earns 25%), or commit $75M annually (earns 18%), or hybrid: $60M 3-year + $25M 1-year = earn 22% blended. Result: negotiate 3-year + 1-year combo to reach target discount with flexibility.","C. Demand 25% (lose AWS partnership)","D. Accept 0% (pay list price)"],"answer":1,"explain":"3-year + 1-year hybrid structure. Blended discount 22%. Flexibility + discount balance. $22M savings achieved."}];